<HEADLINE> Qian: China to Deepen Reform, Widen Opening-Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- China will carry out a
policy of deepening its reform and opening wider to the outside
world, Chinese Vice Premier Qian Qichen told the delegations at
the 52nd session of the United Nations General Assembly today.
</P>
<P>
China is also determined to step up national development and
promote the cause of world peace, said Qian, who is also China's
foreign minister, in addressing the UN session.
</P>
<P>
Qian said the 15th National Congress of the Communist Party of
China came to a triumphant conclusion in Beijing. The Congress,
holding high the great banner of Deng Xiaoping Theory, charts the
future course of China's development with a blueprint, and
displays the resolve to carry forward the cause of building
socialism with Chinese characteristics well into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Qian also said that the resumption of the exercise of
sovereignty over Hong Kong on July 1 wiped out China's national
humiliation of one and a half centuries and opened up a new
chapter in the nation's peaceful reunification.
</P>
<P>
"Over the past two months or more after its return, Hong Kong
has enjoyed social stability and economic prosperity, which fills
the people in Hong Kong, China and the world at large with great
joy," Qian said.
</P>
<P>
The fact that Deng Xiaoping's concept of "one country, two
systems" becomes reality in Hong Kong carries a profound
significance, he said. "Firmly adhering to this concept, we will
keep up the peaceful reunification of our motherland by ensuring a
smooth return of Macao and eventually resolving the Taiwan
question."
</P>
<P>
Qian stressed, "Taiwan is an inalienable part of Chinese
territory and the Taiwan question is purely an internal affair of
China. Any country that attempts to use the Taiwan question to put
pressure on China or even clamors for `two Chinas' or `one China,
one Taiwan,' has acted in total contravention of the purposes and
principles of the UN Charter and the relevant General Assembly
resolutions."
</P>
<P>
Such behavior will be absolutely unacceptable to the Chinese
people as well as all the justice-upholding countries in the
world, stated the Chinese vice premier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
