<HEADLINE> Developing Countries Urged to Give Priority to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Conference
on Trade and Development (UNCTAD) has urged developing countries
to give high priority to agriculture to attain sustainable
growth.
</P>
<P>
In a report released here today UNCTAD said despite being the
most important economic activity in the developing countries,
agriculture has failed to keep pace with population growth.
</P>
<P>
The report said weaknesses in the agriculture sector of such
countries is a result of poor government policies.
</P>
<P>
There has been a lack of political commitment to an efficient
institutional agriculture framework in the developing countries,
it noted.
</P>
<P>
UNCTAD also urged developing countries to promote food
security especially in rural areas where most of the people
depend on agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The report pointed out that the most effective policy to
increase food security in certain developing countries is the
promotion of peace because food insecurity in most developing
countries is caused by internal conflicts.
</P>
<P>
The serious obstacle to agricultural development in developing
countries is lack of credit facilities for farmers, said the
report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
