<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oman Calls for Peace In Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Oman's Minister of State
for Foreign Affairs Yousef Bin Alawi Bin Abdullah said today that
Oman will continue to support a peaceful settlement to the
stalled Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
The minister told the Omani news agency that his country
insisted on a peaceful settlement to the deadlock in the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
He warned that the current status of the Middle East
peace process would benefit nobody but those extremists and all
enemies of peace.
</P>
<P>
The minister also stressed that a return to the negative
Arab-Israeli relations could never contribute to the stability
in the Middle East region, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
The Middle East peace process has been in deadlock since March
this year due to the Israeli construction of a new settlement in
East Jerusalem, which the Palestinians want to be the capital of
a future state.
</P>
<P>
The move has triggered violent clashes between Palestinians
and Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
