<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qian on International Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Expanding military
blocs and enhancing military alliances under new circumstances can
do little to bring about greater security, Chinese Vice Premier
and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen said here today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the 52nd session of the General Assembly of the
United Nations, Qian said relations between states should be based
on the five principles of mutual respect for sovereignty and
territorial integrity, mutual non-aggression, non-interference in
each other's internal affairs, equality and mutual benefit and
peaceful coexistence.
</P>
<P>
"Each country has the right to choose a road of development
according to its own national conditions and no country should
interfere in the internal affairs of other countries on whatever
ground," he said.
</P>
<P>
"This must serve as the political prerequisite for global and
regional security," he emphasized.
</P>
<P>
He said that as the economic foundation for global and regional
security, all countries should increase their mutually-beneficial
cooperation in the economic field, eliminate unequal practices in
trade and economic relations and do way with discriminatory
policies.
</P>
<P>
As a practical way to achieve global and regional security, all
nations should step up consultation and cooperation in the
security field, increase mutual understanding and trust and settle
whatever differences and disputes they may have through peaceful
means, he added.
</P>
<P>
Giving examples of new models of security cooperation, Qian
mentioned the agreement signed by the five countries of China,
Russia, Kazakstan, Tajikistan and Kyrgyzstan in the first half
of the year on mutual reduction of military forces in the border
areas.
</P>
<P>
Other examples include the four-party talks involving China,
the United States, the Democratic People's Republic of Korea and
the Republic of Korea to bring about a new peace mechanism on the
Korean Peninsula, and the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
Regional Forum which introduced a preliminary form of cooperation
on security issues featuring equal participation and negotiated
consensus.
</P>
<P>
He said China feels concerned about the recent setbacks in the
Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
"We are of the view that the relevant U.N. resolutions should
be complied with, agreements reached among the parties concerned
in the peace process should be honored, the principles of `land
for peace' should be adhered to and terrorist activities should
stop," Qian said.
</P>
<P>
China hopes that the Conference on Peace in the Middle East
will resume at an early date, he said.
</P>
<P>
Regarding Africa, he said China is deeply concerned about the
incessant conflicts and turmoil which have plagued the continent
since the beginning of this year and wishes the African nations
steady progress along the road of peace and development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
