<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qian Qichen on Arms Control, Disarmament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- China today called for
an overhaul to the discriminatory and exclusive non-proliferation
regimes.
</P>
<P>
In his address to the 52nd session of the General Assembly of
the United Nations, Foreign Minister Qian Qichen said it is
necessary to have a universal participation in the
non-proliferation process.
</P>
<P>
"The U.N. should see that it accomplishes something in this
regard," said Qian who is also vice premier.
</P>
<P>
"In our view, no one should try to monopolize the market under
the name of preventing proliferation and to interfere in the
economic and technological cooperation of other countries,
developing countries in particular," he said.
</P>
<P>
Continued efforts should be made to advance the process of
multilateral arms control and disarmament and the universality of
international arms control treaties should be strengthened and
their complete adherence ensured," Qian added.
</P>
<P>
"The target of disarmament should not be shifted to developing
nations as countries with the largest and most sophisticated
arsenals bear a special responsibility for disarmament," he
emphasized.
</P>
<P>
Turning to China's disarmament move, he drew the Assembly's
attention to China's recent announcement of a unilateral step in
this regard.
</P>
<P>
On the basis of the reduction of 1 million troops in the 1980s,
China will further reduce its military by 500,000 troops within
the next three years, he said.
</P>
<P>
"This is a move of major importance in the field of
disarmament," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
