<DOCNO> XIE19970925.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Ready to Forge Cross-Century Ties with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA-ATA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chinese Premier Li
Peng said here today that China is ready to work with Kazakhstan
to forge a comprehensive and cooperative partnership toward the
21st century.
</P>
<P>
Li, speaking to reporters along with Kazakh President Nursultan
Abishevich Nazarbayev after their talks, added that to develop
long-term, stable and good-neighborly ties with Kazakhstan
constitutes an important part of China's foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
Li and Nazarbayev attended the signing ceremony of an oil
contract following their talks.
</P>
<P>
Li noted that the oil contract "opened a new page" in the
bilateral relations between the two nations.
</P>
<P>
China's increasing demand of petroleum due to its economic
growth and the rich oil reserve in Kazakhstan predict further
expansion of cooperation in the petroleum sector between the two
countries, Li said.
</P>
<P>
Nazarbayev noted that Kazakh-Chinese relations have been
growing steadily in recent years. He added that the
"cross-century" cooperative agreement signed today will fuel the
development of bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
He said China's rapidly-growing economy provides a big market
for Kazakhstan. He added that his country will take this
opportunity to enhance the economic and trade ties with China.
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan's policy is to establish friendly relations of
mutual trust and all-round cooperation with China, the president
said.
</P>
<P>
According to Nazarbayev, Kazakhstan-China trade volume in 1996
was over 500 million U.S. dollars. He predicted this figure will
be in billions of dollars in the years to come.
</P>
<P>
Li, who had just attended the annual meetings of the World Bank
and the International Monetary Fund in Hong Kong, said the
meeting left him with the impression that the world economy is
becoming more and more inter-dependent.
</P>
<P>
To further strengthen relations with Kazakhstan and other CIS
states will benefit the development of economy and improvement of
the people's living standards in China and all these countries,
and will be conducive to the world trend of multipolarization as
well, the premier said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
