<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Enforce Tight Monetary Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The Reserve Bank of Zimbabwe
(RBZ) today announced its intention to maintain a tight monetary
policy for the remainder of this year in light of the underlying
inflationary pressures that continue to rock the southern African
economy.
</P>
<P>
RBZ Governor Leonard Tsumba said in a monetary policy
statement that the conduct of monetary policy would continue to
be dictated by developments on the inflation front.
</P>
<P>
"The conduct of monetary policy for the remainder of the year
and part of next year will be influenced, to a large degree, by
pressures on the growth in money supply which will be a function
of the financing of the 1997/98 budget deficit and the impact of
wage settlements," he said.
</P>
<P>
The thrust of the monetary policy would be to reduce the
growth in reserve money with a view to controlling monetary
expansion and inflation which was pegged at 18 percent in August,
Tsumba said.
</P>
<P>
Inflationary pressures arising from increases in fuel and
education fees, together with high growth in money supply,
prompted the Central Bank to tighten its monetary policy stance
in May this year.
</P>
<P>
The announcement today came on the back of recent measures to
curtail money supply expansion which saw the Central Bank
introducing new clearing and settlement arrangements for
commercial banks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970925.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rapid Economic Growth Predicted for Sub-Sahara </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has projected
that countries in sub-Sahara Africa are poised for rapid economic
growth in the next decade.
</P>
<P>
In a report titled "Global Economic Prospects and the
Developing World for 1997" reaching here today, the bank said 25
countries in the sub-region have achieved economic growth of
nearly seven percent in the past successive three years.
</P>
<P>
The report said sub-Sahara Africa, which suffered negative per
capita income growth over the past decade, is projected to
achieve positive growth in the next decade.
</P>
<P>
"The outlook for developing countries looks much more
favorable over the next 10 years than in the previous decade," it
noted.
</P>
<P>
According to the World Bank, the international economic
environment for the developing countries remains favorable,
characterized by broadly stable world macro-economic conditions,
increasing flow of private capital to them.
</P>
<P>
Private capital flow to developing countries reached a record
245 billion U.S. dollars last year, said the report.
</P>
<P>
"In sub-Sahara Africa where some 25 countries are undertaking
structural adjustment and economic reform, recent growth has
exceeded four percent in the past two years, economic growth was
nearly seven percent for the third year in a row," the report
added.
</P>
<P>
Three developing regions that suffered negative per capita
income growth over the past decade, namely the sub-Sahara Africa
and Middle East, North Africa and East Europe, as well as Central
Asia, are projected to achieve positive growth in the next
decade.
</P>
<P>
The next 25 years will see an unprecedented boost in the
prominence of developing countries in the world economy and five
of these countries -- Brazil, China, India, Indonesia and Russia
-- are projected to fundamentally change the way the world does
business, the bank predicted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
