<DOCNO> XIE19970925.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Sets up Task Force for Impact Evaluation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization
(WHO) set up a task force today to evaluate the impact of its
programs on member countries, according to the agency's Africa
regional office Director Ebrahim Samba.
</P>
<P>
"We set up a small task force to define the parameters of
impact evaluation," Samba told the Zimbabwe News Agency, adding
"the task force has six members from WHO's member countries."
</P>
<P>
"This is the first time WHO has looked into impact
evaluation," Samba noted.
</P>
<P>
The task force would set the framework for the evaluation
exercise. In the past WHO used to evaluate what was done without
assessing the impact.
</P>
<P>
The agency's representatives are meeting here to review its
activities in the African region over the past year and prepare
individual country programs of action for the 1998/99 period.
</P>
<P>
The agency has 46 offices in the region, with the headquarters
moved to Zimbabwe in the aftermath of the civil war in Congo
Brazzaville. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
