<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNCTAD Urges Poor Nations to Develop Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Conference on Trade
and Development (UNCTAD) today urged the world's most impoverished
nations to prioritize their often neglected agricultural sector if
they want to attain and sustain high growth rates.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture is the most important economic activity in the
LDCs, the UNCTAD noted in "The Least Developed Countries (LDCs)
Report-1997" launched here today.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture provided about one-third of their collective gross
domestic product (GDP) and employed two-thirds of the labor force
at the start of the 1990s, but its performance has failed to keep
pace with population growth, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It pointed out that a robust agriculture policy is also a key
to an integrated poverty alleviation strategy, as the poorer
people in the LDCs tend to live in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that the LDCs report has been launched
outside Geneva and in Dhaka, capital of the largest of the 48
countries designated by the United Nations as least developed.
</P>
<P>
The visiting UNCTAD Secretary-General Rubens Ricupero said at
the launching ceremony that his organization has chosen Bangladesh
for releasing the report to pay tribute to its championing role in
the causes of the LDCs.
</P>
<P>
He praised Bangladesh for raising a strong voice in addressing
the problems of the LDCs and stressed that some integrated
approaches must be adopted for better access of LDCs' products to
world market.
</P>
<P>
The LDCs report pointed out however that growth among the
world's LDCs remained relatively robust at an average of 4.7
percent in 1996 compared with 5.2 percent in l995.
</P>
<P>
The slight decline is due mainly to a slowdown in the average
growth rate of the 33 African LDCs, from 5.4 percent in 1995 to
4.6 percent in 1996, the report continued. For the LDCs in Asia
and Pacific islands, the average growth rate rose slightly from
4.6 percent in 1995 to 4.8 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The report said institutional and economic reforms were
generating strong growth in many LDCs and pointed out that the
Asian LDCs have benefited from their location in the world's
fastest-growing region.
</P>
<P>
The largest LDC, Bangladesh, has not performed as well as might
have been hoped, the report said, adding that this is partly due
to a delay in the implementation of economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
The 213-page report pleaded for urgent action by the
international community to help the LDCs tackle their widespread
problems such as economic and social regress and internal conflict
on a priority basis.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
