<DOCNO> XIE19970925.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Refuses Israeli Charges Over Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Bethlehem, Palestine, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat today denied the
Israeli charges that he should be responsible for the recent two
suicide bombing attacks in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question at the joint news conference with
visiting Czech President Vaclav Havel, Arafat said that the
Israeli investigations into the July 30 Mahane Yehuda bombing and
the September 4 Ben Yehuda bombing in central Jerusalem showed
that the terrorists came from Area B and Area C under
"overridding Israeli responsibility" instead of Area A under the
Palestinian control.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday night, Israel announced that it had uncovered the
identities of four of the five suicide bombers carrying out the
two Jerusalem bombing attacks that killed 25 people and wounded
300 others. They all came from the Azira Shamalya village, near
Nablus in West Bank, which is within Area B under Israeli total
security control.
</P>
<P>
They, all members of the Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas),
had been jailed by the PNA last year, but later escaped from
prison to go underground until carrying out the attacks.
</P>
<P>
Israel still held Arafat for being responsible for the
bombings because the planners behind the attacks came from Area
A. Deputy Israeli Defense Minister Silvan Shalom asserted in the
Knesset (Parliament) that the terror cell that planned the
bombings are living in Area A which is under total Palestinian
control.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting between Israeli and Palestinian security
officials held in Ramallah Tuesday night, Israel handed over a
list of terror suspects to the Palestinian side to demand for
their arrests.
</P>
<P>
Contrary to Israeli charges that he is not doing enough to
combat terror, Arafat insisted that he is doing 100 percent
efforts to fight terrorism according to the obligations of the
signed peace accords, but he could not guarantee 100 percent
results.
</P>
<P>
Arafat added that he should not be responsible for the two
Jerusalem bombings just because the suicide bombers were those
who escaped from Palestinian prisons. "They escaped, what could
I do?" he asked.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the media rumors about his deteriorating
health, Arafat said that he did not need to answer the question
because Israelis were also against him, his authority and his
people.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli security forces continued the sweeping
crackdown against suspected terrorists in Azira Shamalya and
other villages in the West Bank, arresting dozens more Islamic
militants. Israel Radio said that Palestinian police have also
detained 20 Hamas activists.
</P>
<P>
The latest arrests brought to over 600 the number of Islamic
militants who have been detained by Israel since the Jerusalem
bombings for being involved in terrorist activities against
Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
