<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier on Human Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice Premier
and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen said here today that the
universality of human rights should be respected, but their
realization must be integrated with national conditions.
</P>
<P>
"The realization of human rights is the common ideal of
mankind," said Qian in addressing the 52nd session of the United
Nations General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Qian said all countries have made great efforts to this end,
with both achievements and lessons. "We maintain that the
universality of human rights should be respected, yet their
realization must be integrated with the conditions of each
country."
</P>
<P>
A review of the UN practice in the past 50 years and more shows
that when countries or regions do likewise, they will enjoy social
stability, economic development and popular contentment, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Conversely, society will face disintegration where people will
lose their most basic human rights and freedoms, and gross
violations of human rights will even take place when chaos erupts
as a result of war," added Qian.
</P>
<P>
It is quite natural for people to differ on the human rights
issue and the question is how to deal with these differences, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"Only dialogue can enhance mutual understanding and
cooperation. Confrontation on the other hand can only lead to
further estrangement and do nobody any good. We are pleased to see
that more and more countries are in favor of dialogue in handling
the human rights issue," the Chinese vice premier said.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese Government attaches importance to human rights and
is dedicated to promoting and protecting human rights of its
people," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Having repeatedly suffered from foreign aggression in the
past, the Chinese people know full well how state sovereignty and
territorial integrity fundamentally guarantee the realization of
their human rights," Qian said.
</P>
<P>
He said, "We in China, taking upon ourselves the task of
feeding, clothing, sheltering, educating and providing travel
facilities to our 1.2 billion people, know full well how vitally
important our right to subsistence and right to development are."
</P>
<P>
To enable the Chinese people to lead a freer, happier and more
democratic life, "we focus our utmost on the development of
economy and the improvement of democracy and legal system," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese vice premier declared that China will soon sign the
International Covenant on Economic, Social and Cultural Rights and
is studying earnestly the International Covenant on Civil and
Political Rights.
</P>
<P>
"We stand ready to work with other countries in a continued
effort to promote cooperation in the international human rights
field," said Qian. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970925.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
