<HEADLINE> Fighting Continues in Key Afghan Border Town </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Fighting between the Afghan
Taliban militia and their rival forces was continuing to rage in a
strategic Afghan town bordering Uzbekistan today, Afghan sources
said.
</P>
<P>
Forces loyal to the anti-Taliban northern alliance today
launched a three-pronged attack on Hairatan, which separates
Afghanistan from its Central Asian neighbor Uzbekistan, said the
Afghan sources in Peshawar, Northwest Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The alliance, which comprises forces led by ethnic Uzbek
warlord Abdul Malik, Tajik warlord Ahmad Masood and the Shiite
Hezb-e-Wadhat, has claimed that it had captured Sheiak City near
Hairatan from the hands of the Taliban, who entered the town last
week, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
However, the Taliban immediately denied the claim and said they
had repulsed the alliance's offensive and were now moving toward
Mazar-e-Sharif, the stronghold of the anti-Taliban alliance,
according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
Hairatan, situated 60 kilometers north of Mazar-e-Sharif, about
300 kilometers north of Kabul, is a key town located on the banks
of the Amu Darya (Oxus River) on the Uzbek border.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, the Taliban, who control two-thirds of Afghan
territory and the capital of Kabul, briefly controlled the
Mazar-e-Sharif airport, but were forced to retreat in a few days.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
