<HEADLINE> Chirac, Ivorian President Discuss Situation in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
and President Henri Konan Bedie of Cote d'Ivoire discussed today
the situation in the Congo Republic, including the possible
deployment of a pan-African peace-keeping force in Brazzaville.
</P>
<P>
"We talked about a force of mutual security, an inter-posing
force, a peace-keeping force for the whole region of West Africa,
including French-speaking, English-speaking, Portuguese-speaking
and Spanish-speaking countries," said Bedie after having a dinner
with Chirac at the Elysee Palace.
</P>
<P>
France Tuesday again asked United Nations Secretary General
Kofi Annan to arrange the deployment of a peace-keeping force in
the capital of the Congo Republic Brazzaville, where fighting has
been going on between the forces of President Pascal Lissouba and
former Congolese President General Denis Sassou-Nguesso.
</P>
<P>
At least 4,000 people have been killed in the fighting over the
past four months in Brazzaville.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Security Council has not given its
greenlight to the sending of a pan-African peace-keeping force
backed with logistics from France and some other European Union
countries. 
</P>
