<HEADLINE> Mubarak Returns Home From Russia Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak returned home this afternoon, concluding a three-day visit
to Russia for talks with his Russian counterpart Boris Yeltsin on
the Middle East situation.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa who accompanied Mubarak
to Russia told Egyptian reporters in Moscow that the visit is
"positive" at both political and economic levels, the Egyptian
Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Russia has reaffirmed its commitment to the land-for-peace
principle adopted at the U.S.-Russian sponsored peace conference
in Madrid in October 1991, and its full awareness of the negative
role of the Israeli policies that has led the peace process come
to a standstill since March, Moussa said.
</P>
<P>
The Russian side had clearly said that the current situation
required an urgent initiative to rescue the peace process, and
that Russia would join efforts for that end, according to Moussa.
</P>
<P>
Another outcome of the visit is an upcoming Middle East tour
by Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov in the coming weeks,
which includes Egypt, Moussa said.
</P>
<P>
In the economic domain, seven bilateral agreements had been
signed between the two countries, particularly with regard to
prevention of dual taxation and investment guarantees, he added.
</P>
<P>
On Mubarak's talks in Moscow with U.S. Vice President Al Gore,
Moussa said the talks covered several issues, including bilateral
relations, the Middle East peace process and the continued
international sanctions against Libya.
</P>
<P>
As for the U.S. disregard of the Arab League decision to
alleviate sanctions against Libya, Moussa said that the
alleviation of sanctions fell within the terms of reference of the
U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
He demanded Arab states, the Organization of African Unity and
the non-aligned countries make efforts for lifting the siege on
the Libyan people, which was imposed in 1992 for Libya's failure
to hand over two suspects allegedly involved in the bombing of a
Pan Am jetliner over Lockbie, Scotland in 1988, which killed 270
people on board.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian foreign minister left Moscow today for New York
to attend the U.N. General Assembly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
