<HEADLINE> Tran Duc Luong Elected Vietnamese President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Tran Duc Luong, 60, was elected
today president of Vietnam and Nong Duc Manh, 57, re-elected
chairman of the National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Tran Duc Luong, born in May 5, 1937, in central Vietnam's Guang
Ngai Province, was elected with 97.78 percent of the votes,
official Vietnamese news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Tran Duc Luong had been Vietnam's deputy prime minister since
1982.
</P>
<P>
Nong Duc Manh was re-elected with 98.44 percent of the votes.
</P>
<P>
The National Assembly also elected four vice-chairmen and a
vice-chairwoman. The four vice-chairmen are Nguyen Van Yeu, Mai
Thuc Lan, Nguyen Phuc Thanh and Vu Dinh Cu. The vice-chairwoman is
Truong My Hoa.
</P>
<P>
Sources here said the National Assembly is to elect Vietnam's
new prime minister and other senior government officials
tommorrow. 
