<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qian, Albright Meet for Chinese President's US Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier and
Foreign Minister Qian Qichen Tuesday night met with U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright on the preparation for
Chinese President Jiang Zemin's up-coming state visit to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
The two sides reviewed the recent positive progress in the
bilateral relations and agreed that more efforts are needed for
greater progress in the commonly concerned areas so as to ensure
the visit successful and boost Sino-U.S. relations to a new stage
of development.
</P>
<P>
Qian and Albright discussed in depth relating matters effecting
the bilateral ties. They agreed to keep such regular contacts,
which would benefit the improvement and development of the
relations.
</P>
<P>
The two sides held that peaceful utilization of nuclear energy
conforms to the common and long-term interests of the two peoples.
They agreed to continue their efforts for an early implementation
of the Sino-U.S. agreement on the cooperation in peaceful
utilization of nuclear energy.
</P>
<P>
On China's accession to the World Trade Organization (WTO),
they agreed that the two sides should redouble their efforts to
settle their differences in the bilateral talks to achieve
substantive progress.
</P>
<P>
Qian reiterated China's position on the question of Taiwan. He
stressed that the question of Taiwan has always been a key issue
in Sino-U.S. relations. China hopes the U.S. will honor the
principle enshrined in the three joint communiques, handle the
question of Taiwan with prudence, and no longer allow this
question to interfere with the progress and development of the
bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
He said that Chinese President Jiang Zemin restated China's
principled position on the question of Taiwan at the 15th National
Congress of the Communist Party of China. "Peaceful reunification
and one country, two systems" remains the principle of China in
resolving the question of Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Albright said that the U.S. side understands China's concern
over the question of Taiwan and will handle the question with
prudence.
</P>
<P>
She stressed that the U.S. government will adhere to the
principle of the three joint communiques and clearly and
unmistakenly pursue a "one China" policy, that will be the basis
in its China policy and in handling the question of Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
She stated that the United State will never be for "two
Chinas," "one China, one Taiwan" or Taiwan's independence, nor
support Taiwan's attempt to gain access to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
She declared that her country will only have non-official
contacts with Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also exchanged views on the United Nations and
other international and regional issues of common concern.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970925.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seminar on Future ACP-EU Relations Held in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- A seminar deliberating
on the future relations between African, Caribbean and Pacific
(ACP) countries and the European Union (EU) following the expiry
of the Lome IV Convention in the year 2000 was held here today.
</P>
<P>
Opening the seminar which was organized by the Ethiopian
Chamber of Commerce, Aschalew Haile, vice-president of the
Ethiopian Chamber of Commerce said the Lome Convention
consolidated ACP-EU relationship which was largely based on the
existence of mutual interests between the then members of the
European Community and of the ACP group.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, the globalization of the world economy has
upset the relationship.
</P>
<P>
Haile said Ethiopia has been signatory to the Lome Convention
since Lome I, 1975 and ever since then, the country has benefited
considerably from the various aid instruments provided under the
cooperation framework.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, he noted, in the area of trade, although the
convention grants non-reciprocal free access to the community
market, Ethiopia could not make use of the advantage because of
the structural rigidity of its export sector reflected on lack of
export diversification.
</P>
<P>
In his speech at the seminar, Italian Ambassador to Ethiopia
Maurizio Melani said ACP countries' share in the world market is
now only two percent and Africa's share in the world investment
sector is not more than four percent.
</P>
<P>
He called on African nations to settle political differences
peacefully in a bid to promote the continent's share in trade and
investment.
</P>
<P>
Presenting to the workshop a "green paper" which reflects EU's
ideas on its relations with ACP, the EU delegation urged the
contracting parties to take a fresh look at the future of ACP-EU
relations before the convention expires in the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
