<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Leader Calls for Reduction of Traffic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian
Vice-President Omar Ali Juma today called for a reduction of road
accidents in the country.
</P>
<P>
Traffic accidents in Tanzania cost the government about 11
billion Shillings (17.5 million US Dollars) per year, leaving
alone the sufferings inflicted on the victims and value added to
reflect grief and pain to the relatives, said Juma in a speech
read at a function here today.
</P>
<P>
Juma noted that despite the government's initiatives to
introduce speed limiters and severe penalties to reckless drivers
to reduce the rate of road accidents, the measures have not
succeeded to alleviate the problem.
</P>
<P>
Special attention must be given to more effective training,
testing and licensing procedures to flush out bad drivers from
the roads, he said.
</P>
<P>
Juma urged drivers, transport operators and other road users
to observe traffic rules and regulations and respect other road
users.
</P>
<P>
He warned drivers not to drive when in fatigue or under the
influence of alcohol or drugs. 
</P>
