<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latvian PM Visits NATO Headquarters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Latvian Prime Minister
Guntars Krasts said today that only the North Atlantic alliance
together with the European Union can guarantee the security of the
Baltic state.
</P>
<P>
Krasts made this remark at the end of his first visit to the
headquarters of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization. He
described his visit as an "historical moment."
</P>
<P>
"Only NATO and the European Union can guarantee Latvian
development in the future in a stable and secure atmosphere," he
said at a post-visit press briefing.
</P>
<P>
During his one-day visit, the Latvian prime minister met and
discussed bilateral relations with NATO Secretary General Javier
Solana and delivered a speech to a North Atlantic Council session.
</P>
<P>
While addressing NATO council members, the Latvian prime
minister said that he was glad to visit the NATO headquarters but
his nation's ultimate goal is to reach further than being just a
visitor.
</P>
<P>
He said that his country is making NATO-oriented adjustment and
he believed that one day Latvia will be among those who are at the
NATO headquarters to welcome him.
</P>
<P>
Krasts exchanged views with Solana on what to do to improve the
current military hardware of Latvia so as to meet the accession
requirement of NATO.
</P>
<P>
The NATO chief briefed the visitor about the latest development
of the NATO agenda that could well include the accession
negotiations currently underway between Hungary, Poland, the Czech
Republic and NATO.
</P>
<P>
Like Hungary, Poland and the Czech Republic, the three Baltic
countries also applied for NATO membership. Yet Russia is firmly
opposed to the accession to NATO by Baltic states Latvia, Estonia
and Lithuania.
</P>
<P>
Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov said Tuesday in New
York that Russia will be responsible for the security of the
Baltic states.
</P>
<P>
When asked to comment on Primakov's statement, the Latvian
prime minister said that the issue of Latvian security is a rather
complicated one.
</P>
<P>
While commenting on the scenario of just one Baltic state
joining the 15-nation military alliance, the NATO chief said that
Madrid is only the beginning of the NATO enlargement. It is not
the end of it, he said.
</P>
<P>
NATO invited Hungary, Poland and the Czech Republic to join the
North Atlantic alliance at its Madrid summit held on July 8 and 9.
</P>
<P>
The NATO chief, who praised Latvia for its positive
participation in the NATO-led Stabilization Force (SFOR) in Bosnia
and Partnership for Peace program, reaffirmed at the briefing that
those countries that wish to join and are qualified to join can do
so in future, in that enlargement is an open process and the
alliance will welcome other newcomers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
