<HEADLINE> UAE Completes Amendments to Copyright Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates
(UAE) has completed amendment to the Copyright Law to make it
tougher for violators, the WAM News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The amended copyright law would be implemented after being
approved by UAE'S Council of Ministers at the end of this year,
the agency quoted a senior official of the Ministry of Information
and Culture which was responsible for the work of amendment.
</P>
<P>
"We have prepared the amendments because it is obvious to us
that some articles should be changed to match international
agreements," the official said.
</P>
<P>
The WAM report gave no details about the amendments, which
observers here said would most likely include some modifications
in current penalties for violators.
</P>
<P>
UAE drew up in 1992 the Copyright Law which allows a one-year
grace period for violators to amend their status.
</P>
<P>
Foreign businessmen, however, claimed that the law was less
than strict and effective for violators.
</P>
<P>
"The current penalties are not effective. We have seen
companies which committed piracy seven times and the Ministry (of
Information and Culture) knows them well," said Sharma, spokesman
of the Business Software Alliance in Middle East based in Abu
Dhabi.
</P>
<P>
He said "The UAE should impose harsher penalties on second or
third violations. This could make the law meet international
agreements." 
</P>
</TEXT>
