<HEADLINE> Taylor Unable to Attend U.N. General Assembly for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Liberian President Charles
Talyor is unable to attend the current session of the U.N.
General Assembly due to "insecurity", a report reaching here said
today.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted state-controlled radio ELBC as saying
Tuesday in Monrovia that the senate, which normally approves
foreign trips of the president, declined to give permission to
Taylor to go to New York, where was expected to address the
General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The senate reportedly said in a letter to Taylor that the
decision was based on "the peculiarities and uncertainties
surrounding the president's safety and security during his visit
to the U.S.."
</P>
<P>
The report implied that Taylor would not travel to the U.S.
because an arrest warrant issued by a Massachusetts court was
awaiting him.
</P>
<P>
Taylor broke out of a Boston jail in 1984, where was being
held pending extradition on charges laid by the then Liberian
government that he had embezzled some one million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
But reports reaching here earlier said a district court in
Boston has already dismissed the extradition request on Monday.
</P>
<P>
It said Monrovia earlier this month sent a note to the U.S.
authorities saying it had "withdrawn its request for the
extradition of Mr. Taylor."  
</P>
