<HEADLINE> 1st Asia-Europe Fiber-Optics Phone Cable to Be </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The first intercontinental
fiber-optics telecom cable directly linking Frankfurt of Germany
with Shanghai of China will become operational by the end of this
year, Germany's telecom giant Deutsche Telekom announced today.
</P>
<P>
According to a spokesman of Deutsche Telekom, the fiber-optics
link, called Trans-Asia-Europe-Line (TAE), would be 17,000
kilometers long, runing from Shanghai through Kazakhstan,
Uzbekistan, Turkmenistan, Iran, Turkey, Bulgaria, Hungary, Austria
to Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
Combined with national networks along the stretch, the cable
will be developed into a huge intercontinental network covering 20
countries in Asia and Europe.
</P>
<P>
Built by a consortium of telecom companies, including Deutsche
Telekom and China Telecom, the cable will be able to carry voice
telephony and data traffic with a 155-megabit capacity, equivalent
to between 13,000 and 15,000 simultaneous telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
The total investment on the TAE would run up to about 560
million U.S. dollars, Deutsche Telekom said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
