<HEADLINE> Most of Ethiopia's Potentially Irrigable Land </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Abdulreshid Dulane,
Ethiopian Vice-Minister of Water Resources today warned that only
160,000 of the country's 3.5 million hectares of potentially
irrigable area has so far been developed through irrigation.
</P>
<P>
He made the statement when opening a workshop here.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia enjoys various potentially irrigable basins which are
capable of significantly contributing to undertakings of small
and medium scale agricultural development projects, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia's agricultural sector, dominated by small scale
holders, may cause increased problem of food security when
compared with the fast growing population.
</P>
<P>
The vice minister called for increased efforts in soil and
water protection in drought prone areas, planting of fast growing
crops, and employment of modern agricultural inputs as
intervention measures to combat reduction of food production.
</P>
<P>
The workshop was organized to support the capacity building
effort of the Somali Region Sustainable Development of
Agriculture and Environmental Rehabilitation Commission set up
last week. 
</P>
