<DOCNO> XIE19970925.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada-US Dairy Dispute Expected to Flare Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- A long-running dispute between
Canada and the U.S. over dairy products is set to flare up again
next week when Canada is included in a U.S. list of countries
targeted for trade disputes.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky is expected to
include the Canadian dairy industry's new export pricing system in
the "301 list" to be subject to U.S. trade actions, said a report
today.
</P>
<P>
Canada's dairy industry adopted a new pricing system for milk
in 1995, which prices milk used for products being exported much
lower than milk used in its domestic market.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. dairy industry has demanded that Barshefsky file a
complaint with the World Trade Organization, arguing that Canada's
pricing system is a disguised subsidy.
</P>
<P>
As a result, Canada's cheese exports to Japan increased 717
percent in the first half of this year because Canada undercuts
U.S. cheese prices by 500 U.S. dollars a ton, the industry argued.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Canada refuses to allow the U.S. dairy
industry any substantial access to its domestic market and uses
tariffs as high as 350 percent to keep out imports, it added.
</P>
<P>
"We note that Canada's dairy trade balance went from a deficit
of 19 million dollars in 1993 to a surplus of 68 million dollars
in 1996," the industry said.
</P>
<P>
Under industry pressure, Barshefsky is widely expected to
launch the complaint against Canada, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, the U.S. lost a NAFTA panel ruling that
found Canada's new import tariffs on dairy did not violate the
free trade agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
