<HEADLINE> U.S. to Appraise Cyprus Issue: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Presidential Emissary
for Cyprus, Richard Holbrooke, said today that the United States
is trying to define the substance of the Cyprus issue, Cyprus News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"We are not on the edge of a historic breakthrough. We are not
in the middle of a Camp David or a Dayton type negotiation. We are
trying to define the issues." He said after meeting with Cypriot
Foreign Minister Ioannis Kasoulides in New York.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke said the parties involved in a settlement to the
Cyprus problem are now in a more productive mood than they were
early this year.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. official said that it is important that Cypriot
President Glafcos Clerides and the Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash will meet in Nicosia to discuss security issues.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders of the Greek and Turkish communities on the
divided island are scheduled to hold talks Friday seeking an
agreement on security issues as demilitarization of the island.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke expressed U.S. support for Cyprus' bid to join the
European Union (EU), but he said it is up to the EU members to
discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
He is expected to meet Clerides when he visits New York in
October to address the U.N. General Assembly, according to the
news agency.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops on the Mediterranean island and took over the northern
third in the wake of a failed coup by the Greek Cypriots seeking
union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared in 1983 a breakaway "Turkish
Republic of Northern Cyprus" recognized only by Turkey, which is
deploying 35,000 troops in northern Cyprus. 
</P>
