<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany's Export Boom Continues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Germany's exports continue the
robust growth by surging nearly 14 percent in July to 78.6 billion
marks (43.9 billion U.S. dollars), the German federal statistics
office announced today.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Germany's imports also increased by about 15 percent
to 67.5 billion marks (37.7 billion dollars) so that the country's
July trade surplus was 11.1 billion marks (6.2 billion dollars)
compared with 10.2 billion (5.7 billion dollars) a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Taking the first seven months of 1997 as a whole, the country's
exports totaled 502.5 billion marks (280.7 billion dollars), up
11.5 percent from the same period of last year. The country's
imports also increased by 9 percent to 433.9 billion marks (242.4
billion dollars) in the same period.
</P>
<P>
Measured against last year's data, Germany's trade surplus in
the first seven months rose from 52.8 billion (29.5 billion
dollars) to 68.6 billion marks (38.3 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the surplus in visible trade, Germany's long-standing
current account deficit, which also included trade in services,
was reduced to 7.8 billion marks (4.4 billion dollars) in the
first seven months of this year from 12.2 billion marks (6.8
billion dollars) a year ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
