<HEADLINE> Germany Calls for Support to Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- African countries will
continue to be the focal point of Germany's development
cooperation, German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the 52nd session of the United Nations General
Assembly, Kinkel said many positive developments have taken place
in Africa in recent years, "a fact which is often overlooked."
</P>
<P>
African states are making significant efforts to settle
conflicts in several countries, he said, adding that the
international community must keep supporting these efforts.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel said Germany, which has canceled debts of over 9 billion
marks (5 billion US dollars) incurred by the least developed
countries since 1978, and in the 1991-1995 period it made
available 16.3 billion marks (9 billion dollars) for Africa's
sub-Saharan nations.
</P>
<P>
On the environment issue, Kinkel said Germany intends to cut
its greenhouse gas emissions by 25 percent by 2010, based on 1900
levels.
</P>
<P>
He expressed Germany's intention to house the Secretariat of
the Convention to Combat Desertification. The convention is to be
held two weeks away.
</P>
<P>
He mentioned Germany's interest in becoming a permanent member
of the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
"If elected, we will be able to make a good contribution," he
said. 
</P>
