<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Government Accused of Demolishing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 24 (Xinhua) -- An Israeli human rights
group today accused the Likud government of launching a punitive
campaign of destroying Palestinian houses since the July 30
double suicide bombings in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference here, spokesman of Israeli Information
Center for Human Rights in Occupied Territories (BTSELEN) said
that in August, Israel destroyed 29 homes in the West Bank, four
times more than that of July and left 163 Palestinians homeless.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman noted that since the beginning of the year,
about 110 Palestinian structures have been demolished in Area C
in the West Bank, which is under sole Israeli control.
</P>
<P>
He said that in the past 10 years, some 1,800 homes of
Palestinians have been demolished in the territories, leaving a
total of 11,000 people homeless.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government has asserted that most of the
demolished buildings were uninhabited incomplete structures and
some of the residential and industrial buildings were destroyed
as buildings without necessary permit.
</P>
<P>
However, Yuval Inbal, a BTSELEN official, argued today that
the reason for the demolition in Area C is not purely
administrative, saying that the demolition has a lot to do with
such considerations as keeping Palestinian buildings away from
Jewish settlements.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the illegality of the buildings, Inbal said that
these houses were built without permit, but getting a permit was
practically impossible, because Israel wants to avoid Palestinian
representation in the area.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that the Palestinian population in the West
Bank has an annual increase of 6 percent, and people living there
have to build new homes.
</P>
<P>
After capturing the West Bank in the 1967 Middle East War,
Israel declared much of the area "state lands" and routinely
rejects Arab ownership claims. 
</P>
</TEXT>
