<HEADLINE> Arab League Condemns Terror Attacks in Algeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League today strongly
condemned the attacks by terrorist gangs against innocent
civilians in Algeria and called for international efforts to
eradicate terrorism.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued today, the Cairo-based organization
described the crimes as "contradictory with heavenly doctrines and
humanitarian principles and values."
</P>
<P>
The 22-member Arab League voiced support to the Algerians in
their efforts in uprooting terrorist groups.
</P>
<P>
The statement also urged the international community to
eradicate terrorism worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Cairo-based Arab Human Rights Organization also
condemned the massacres in the Algerian capital of Algiers that
claimed the lives of hundreds of civilians in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
In an appeal circulated today, the organization called upon
violent groups in Algeria to cease the vicious cycle of violence
that threatens the country's future.
</P>
<P>
It urged all parties and civilian community organizations in
Algeria to clearly proclaim their absolute rejection of violence
and terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Eighty-five people -- some reports put the number at 200 --
were killed and 69 others injured in the latest massacre in the
vicinity of Algiers Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic militants launched their insurgency in 1992 after
the army canceled a parliamentary vote the Islamic Salvation Front
was poised to win. More than 60,000 people have died in violence
ever since. 
</P>
