<HEADLINE> Mexican Foreign Minister on UN Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITRED NATIONS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Mexico, a founding
member of the United Nations, reiterated its full readiness to
contribute to the efforts to reform the Organization, Angel
Gurria, minister of foreign relations of Mexico, said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the 52nd session of the General Assembly, the
foreign minister said Mexico had attacked since 1945 the very
concept of a division between permanent and non-permanent members
of the Security Council, basically because the existence of the
two categories established a discriminatory situation which is
accentuated by giving the permanent members the right of veto, a
privilege which had been abused.
</P>
<P>
He said the need to increase the capability of the United
Nations to prevent conflicts and resolve those that exist required
not only reform of the Security Council and its working methods,
but also a strengthening of the mechanisms for resolving conflicts
through peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said reform of the Security Council was
needed in order to correct the imbalances in its current position,
improve the decision-making mechanism and make the conduct of its
work more transparent.
</P>
<P>
On the financial situation of the Organization, the foreign
minister said that it stemmed from a failure to comply with the
obligations derived from the Charter. The current financial
situation had no link with the assessment system. The road to deal
with it was full, timely and unconditional payment of the
assessments the General Assembly assigned to the member states.
</P>
</TEXT>
