<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Says Agreement on US Anti-Cuba Law Hard to Reach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Trade Commissioner Sir
Leon Brittan of the European Union (EU) said today that it was
still difficult to settle a dispute with Washington over a U.S.
law aimed at curbing foreign investment in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
The Helms-Burton law seeking to punish companies investing in
confiscated Cuban property, and the D'Amato Law seeking to curb
investments in Libya and Iran were hurting trans-Atlantic
relations, Brittan told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"This dispute should be brought to an end," Brittan said. "It
is damaging the relationship and it is damaging the rest of the
world."
</P>
<P>
It would be difficult to reach agreement before the October 15
deadline, Brittan said. "I am not saying that the agreement on
Helms-Burton and D'Amato is even within sight as yet. We have a
long way to go in the talks."
</P>
<P>
During a two-day visit to Washington and New York, Brittan
discussed Helms-Burton and other trade issues with U.S. Trade
Representative Charlene Barshefsky and a number of members of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
He met with Under Secretary of State Stuart Eizenstat, who led
U.S. negotiations on Helms-Burton, and was to meet with U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright in New York this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The Helms-Burton law, enacted last year after Cuba shot down
two small planes being flown by Cuban exiles from Miami, targets
companies profiting from property seized by the Cuban government
after the revolution in 1959.
</P>
<P>
The law was widely condemned by the world community including
the U.S. close allies such as the EU, Canada and Japan. The EU
filed a complaint with the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
Last April, the two sides agreed to try to reach a negotiated
settlement in order to avoid a damaging fight in the WTO, which
the U.S. said had no jurisdiction in what it saw as a national
security issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
