<HEADLINE> Irish FM Says Mind Needs Decommissioning for Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Irish Foreign
Minister Ray Burke said today that an ultimate settlement of the
Northern Ireland conflict required a mind change among the
parties, not only the laying down of weapons.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a breakfast meeting with reporters prior to talks
with U.S. National Security Adviser Sandy Berger here, Burke gave
an upbeat assessment of prospects for progress at all-party
Northern Ireland peace talks in Belfast.
</P>
<P>
The Irish and British security forces detected "absolutely no
breakages" in the truce declared by the Irish Republican Army in
July, he said.
</P>
<P>
But Burke said persuading the Irish Republican Army to hand
over arsenals that have fueled a 28-year war on British rule was
only part of the key to a settlement.
</P>
<P>
"This talks process is about decommissioning a mind-set rather
than just decommissioning the weapons. What we want to ensure
is... paramilitary factions on both sides will feel the outcome is
a fair and honest compromise," Burke said.
</P>
<P>
Burke, who met President Bill Clinton briefly in New York late
Sunday, said he had expressed Dublin's gratitude for U.S. support
for the Northern Ireland peace talks. 
</P>
