<DOCNO> XIE19970925.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNCTAD Publishes LDCs 1997 Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Although growth rates for the
least developed countries (LDCs) fell in 1996 from 1995, growth
has been relatively robust, and many LDCs have performed well
enough to have recorded real increases in output and real
increases in per capita income.
</P>
<P>
UNCTAD Secretary-General Rubens Ricupero made the statement in
an overview of the Least Developed Countries, 1997 Report
published here today.
</P>
<P>
The average GDP real growth rate for all LDCs in 1996 was 4.7
percent, less than the rate of 5.2 percent in 1995, according to
the 1997 report, prepared by UNCTAD, the United Nations Conference
on Trade and Development.
</P>
<P>
"There has been a very slight difference between the
performance of African and Asian LDCs," Ricupero said. "The LDCs
are an extremely heterogeneous group, however, and the most
significant disparities in performance exist not at a regional but
at a country level, with a difference of over 20 percent between
the highest and lowest GDP growth rates for LDCs."
</P>
<P>
Ricupero believed that the future is looking decidedly brighter
for LDCs in Africa than has been the case for quite some time.
</P>
<P>
Many African countries, including LDCs, have experienced higher
growth rates since 1994: 19 African LDCs have had growth rates in
excess of 4 percent, and 10 of those have had GDP growth rates
higher than 5 percent although the average GDP growth rate of 4.6
percent for African LDCs in 1996 is less than the rate of 5.4
percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
There are indications that this trend is set to continue,
Ricupero said. In many countries, export production has been
increased, inflation rates have been reduced and reform has been
consistently well implemented since the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Asian LDCs have seen their average GDP growth rate rise from
4.6 percent in 1995 to 4.8 percent in 1996. They are believed to
have benefited from their location in the world's fastest-growing
region.
</P>
<P>
The recent dynamism of the larger Asian economies, in
particular India and China, has spilled over into neighboring
LDCs. The output expansion in Cambodia and Laos have been
particularly rapid. The largest LDC, Bangladesh, has not performed
as well as might have been hoped. This is partly due to delays in
the implementation of economic reforms, Ricupero noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970925.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
