<HEADLINE> Mandela Declares Robben Island National Museum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 24 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela today declared the Robben Island, his former prison, a
national monument and a museum, the South African Press Association
(SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Mandela had been kept in the island off Cape Town for 18 years
before he was set free by former president F. W. de Klerk in February
1990.
</P>
<P>
Mandela today opened the Robben Island Museum and unveiled a
national monument plaque.
</P>
<P>
He said in a speech that South Africa's cultural institutions,
particularly its museums, are still portraying blacks in a demeaning
manner and were not reflecting the country's diverse heritage, SAPA
reported.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's museums and monuments had reflected the experiences
and political ideals of a minority to the exclusion of others during
colonialism and apartheid, he said.
</P>
<P>
Home Affairs Minister Mangosuthu Buthelezi, who is also leader of the
Zulu-based Inkatha Freedom Party, and several other cabinet ministers
and parliament members were invited to the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Also invited were former veterans of the notorious prison.
</P>
<P>
However, Marthinus van Schalkwyk, president of the National party,
which implemented ultra-racist policies during the apartheid era, was
not invited, SAPA said.
</P>
<P>
Robben Island, a lepers' colony for some time, became a major
political prison to house anti-apartheid activists in the apartheid
era.
</P>
<P>
Arts and Culture Minister Lionel Mtshali said the island is
also a candidate for a world heritage site.  
</P>
</TEXT>
