<HEADLINE> U.S. Offers $2 Million Reward for Mexico's Drug Kingpin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September (Xinhua) -- The U.S. authorities today
stepped up its pressure on Mexico's most violent drug kingpin by
offering a reward of more than two million U.S. dollars and adding
him to the FBI's most wanted list.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference, FBI Director Louis Freech said
Ramon Arellano Felix, 33, the head of security for a gang run by
five brothers, is charged with drug conspiracy and smuggling in a
sealed federal indictment in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
"He and his associates are responsible for directing numerous
murders in Mexico and the United States" and setting the price of
cocaine, marijuana, methamphetamine and heroin throughout the
U.S., said Thomas Constantine, head of the Drug Enforcement
Administration.
</P>
<P>
Arellano Felix is the most violent of the brothers in the gang,
coordinates recruitment of its well-armed and well-trained guards
and commands its armed operations, according to Constantine.
</P>
<P>
Freeh used the news conference to push legislation, now before
a House committee, giving his agents access to the keys to
commercial encryption devices and software used to scramble
telephone conversations and computer transmissions.
</P>
<P>
"If a workable national solution to the encryption problem is
not enacted soon...we simply will loose our most effective tool
with respect to drug interdiction," Freech said.
</P>
<P>
The two million U.S. dollars reward was posted by the State
Department for the arrest or conviction of Ramon Arellano Felix.
The FBI added a 50,000 U.S. dollars reward as well. 
</P>
</TEXT>
