<HEADLINE> Turkey Slams Russia's Missile Deal With Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- A Senior Turkish official
today criticized Russia's missile deal with Cyprus, according to
local TV and radio reports.
</P>
<P>
The Russian-Cypriot missile deal will negatively affect the
stability of the region, Turkish Deputy Prime Minister Ismet
Sezgin said while meeting a Russian military delegation here.
</P>
<P>
The Russian delegation is here to attend the Third
International Defense Industry and Civil Aviation Fair '97, which
opened Tuesday and attracted more than 200 industrial companies
from 20 countries.
</P>
<P>
Russia's decision to sell missiles to Cyprus is not consistent
with the deep-rooted Russian-Turkish friendship, Sezgin said.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has been accusing Russia of signing an agreement in
January to sell hundreds of missiles to the Cypriot government. It
has threatened to use all necessary means to block the delivery of
the missiles.
</P>
<P>
The Russian side, however, said it has no intention to drop the
missile deal, adding that the Cypriot government has the right to
buy weapons which it needs.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the Mediterranean
island following a failed coup by the Greek Cypriots seeking union
with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared in 1983 a breakaway "Turkish
Republic of Northern Cyprus" recognized only by Turkey, which has
deployed 35,000 troops in northern Cyprus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
