<HEADLINE> U.S. Diplomats to Return to Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The United States has
decided to send back its diplomats to Sudan, which, however, did
not mean any change in poor relations between the two countries,
the State Department officials said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We have determined that the security situation permits
American diplomatic staff to be reassigned to Khartoum," an
official said.
</P>
<P>
But that would only be a small, mid-level group of diplomats
that will station in the capital of Sudan while U.S. ambassador
Timothy Carney and some other staff will continue to stay outside
Sudan, making periodic visits there, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. diplomats left Sudan in Feb. 1996 for fear of "threats and
possible attacks upon American diplomats." the Sudanese government
denied that Americans were in danger and urged Washington to
reconsider.
</P>
<P>
The withdrawal of the U.S. diplomats has not led to a
break-down of the relations with Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The officials said that the return of American diplomats
implied no change in Washington's poor relations with Sudan, and
the United States is seeking to contain the Islamic African
country by increasing military assistance to Sudan's neighbors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
