<DOCNO> XIE19970925.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Set to Attain Budget Criteria for Euro in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- France is set to attain the
public deficit at 3 percent of gross domestic product (GDP) quota
in 1998 to qualify for the European single currency euro,
according to an austerity draft budget law presented today by the
Socialist government.
</P>
<P>
The public deficit will be cut by 26.951 billion francs (4.5
billion U.S. dollars) as compared with 1997, to be limited at
257.869 billion francs (43 billion dollars) in 1998, which is
about 3.05 percent of the GDP, said government spokeswoman
Catherine Trautmann.
</P>
<P>
Public spending in 1998 will be restricted at 1,585.3 billion
francs (264 billion US dollars), 1.36 percent more than 1997,
while inflation is expected at 1.3 percent in 1998 and stood at
1.4 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
The government will raise 14 billion francs (2.3 billion US
dollars) from new taxes to be imposed on households and
enterprises, while all taxes to be collected will take 45.9
percent of the GDP next year.
</P>
<P>
Defense spending will be cut by 8.9 billion francs (1.5 billion
US dollars) in conformity with the professionalization process of
the French armed forces.
</P>
<P>
The government will increase family allowances for couples who
work by 7,000 francs (1,170 dollars) and by 5,000 francs (830
dollars) for families with three children.
</P>
<P>
The budget for interior security, employment, national
education and justice will increase by 3.1 percent to 4
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
