<HEADLINE> Sudanese Officials Prepare for Talks With Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese President Omar
al-Bashir today ordered preparation for negotiations with the main
rebel force operating in southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations on ending the country's 14-year-old war
expected to be held in the Kenyan capital of Nairobi next month
under the sponsorship of the Inter Governmental Authority on
Development and Drought (IGADD).
</P>
<P>
The October negotiations were agreed upon by Sudanese Minister
of Federal General Office Ali Mohammed and Commander Nhial Deng of
the largest rebel faction Sudan People's Liberation Army (SPLA) at
the sideline of an IGADD meeting in Nairobi Monday.
</P>
<P>
The IGADD meeting was attended by the foreign ministers of
Kenya, Uganda, Ethiopia and Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
IGADD, which embraces Sudan, Kenya, Uganda, Ethiopia, Eritrea,
Somalia and Djibouti, has played a mediatory role between the
Sudanese government and John Garang, leader of the SPLA.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed and Deng also expressed in a joint statement their
acceptance of the IGADD's declaration of principles of 1994 for
resolving the southern Sudan question.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese government had earlier rejected the IGADD
principles which call for separating religion from politics and
upholding political pluralism in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Sudanese Vice President el Zubeir Mohammed Salih who
is currently on a visit to southern Sudan addressed an appeal to
Garang to join the peace process in the best interests of security
and stability in southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese government has already signed peace agreements
with seven rebel factions in southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Over a million people have died in violence since 1983 when the
southern rebels took up arms for greater autonomy from the Islamic
North for the Christian and animist south. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
