<HEADLINE> Nigeria Turns Out First Home-Made Car </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The first made-in-Nigeria car
produced by the local Izuogu Motors Ltd. made its debut Tuesday in
Imo state, South Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
According to the company Managing Director Ezekiel Izuogu, the car,
modeled Z-600, was built in about eight years, the News Agency of
Nigeria reported today.
</P>
<P>
The manager did not give further description of the car, but said
the engine was one "that could be put to other uses like agricultural
mechanization, standby electric generators, tricycle manufacture,
among others".
</P>
<P>
He said about 200 million Naira (about 2.4 million U.S. Dollars)
will be needed to put a production line in place and go into mass
production of about 30,000 cars a year.
</P>
<P>
When in mass production, he said, it will cost the average Nigerian
between 150,000 and 180,000 Naira (about 1,800-2,200 U.S. Dollars) per
unit.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurating the car, Chief of General Staff Oladipo Diya, the
number two person of the country, said the even marked "the
commencement of our march toward industrial self-sufficiency.
</P>
<P>
He called on Nigerians to work hard for the relentless task for
self actualization and realization of the country's potentials for
industrialization it possess.
</P>
<P>
Due to the underdevelopment of industry, Nigeria has to depend on
imported manufactured goods to meet its needs ranging from
sophisticated machinery to some daily necessities such as metalware.
</P>
<P>
Cheap fuel has made Nigeria a flourish market for automobiles,
mostly second-handed.
</P>
<P>
Currently the country's biggest car producer is the Peugeot
Automobile Nigeria Ltd, a joint venture with France.
</P>
<P>
But due to the sluggish market, the company only operated at 10
percent of its annual 35,000 unit capacity.  
</P>
</TEXT>
