<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Republican Majority Leader Says House to Take Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Republicans will bring
legislation to overhaul campaign finance rules to the floor of the
U.S. House of Representatives this fall, Majority Leader Dick
Armey said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday Senate leaders, under prodding by President Bill
Clinton, agreed to consider the bipartisan bill sponsored by
Senators John McCain, a Republican, and Russell Feingold, a
Democrat, before adjourning for the year.
</P>
<P>
Armey said "I can't tell you what the configuration will be. I
can't tell you what the timing will be. We will have something on
the floor this fall," he said.
</P>
<P>
Democrat Representative George Miller called Armey's statement
"encouraging." Miller, along with other House democrats, have
been pressuring Republican leaders into allowing a floor debate on
a bill to ban "soft money" -- unregulated large donations to
political parties that have been the focus of campaign overhaul.
</P>
<P>
Armey said that a provision limiting unions' use of members'
dues for political activities would probably be part of any
Republican campaign finance overhaul bill.
</P>
<P>
Many Republicans were angered by the 35 million dollars the
American Federation of Labor and congress of Industrial
Organizations (AFL-CIO) spent last year on behalf of Democratic
causes.
</P>
<P>
Clinton threatened in a letter to Senate leaders Tuesday that
he would keep the Senate in session until the McCain-Feingold bill
got full consideration. Democrats have been concerned that
Majority Leader Trent Lott of Mississippi might bring it up just
before adjournment.
</P>
<P>
Armey described Clinton's threat as a hollow "political point."
</P>
<P>
"The fact of the matter is Senator Lott had indicated his
desire to put something on the floor on campaign finance reform
last week and I had indicated that I had the expectation that we
would do it in the House last week," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
