<HEADLINE> Germany Admits Poor Controls over Beef Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Admitting that its meat controls
are not strict enough to block the banned British beef exports,
Germany today called on its 16 federal states to conduct more
thorough and frequent surveillance of their slaughterhouses.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference in Bonn, German Health Minister
Horst Seehofer also accused Britain of not carrying out proper
meat controls of its own and called on the European Commission to
first of all keep a close watch on meat export surveillance in
that country.
</P>
<P>
Seehofer made the remarks in reaction to a EU report on Tuesday
which called for the closure of a German firm after inspectors
found suspected British beef imports in Germany.
</P>
<P>
Bonn has been a staunch backer for maintaining the export ban on
British beef which was imposed by the EU in 1996 after Britain
admitted that there was a possible link between the so-called mad
cow disease and its human equivalent, Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease.
</P>
