<HEADLINE> Sierra Leone Teachers Split over Returning to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, September 25 (Xinhua) -- A major split surfaced
today in the ranks of the 18,000-strong Teachers Union in Sierra
Leone following a recent communique issued by the Teachers
National Executive Committee banning teachers from returning to
the classroom in October.
</P>
<P>
A 15-man Special Committee of Educational Stakeholders had
agreed that primary schools should reopen on October 6 and
secondary schools on October 19 but a communique by the Sierra
Leone Teachers Union National Executive urged teachers to "ignore
both dates and continue to stage a stay-home defiance".
</P>
<P>
The executive said teachers will only return to their jobs "if
the military government returns power back to the civilian
government it ousted and all outstanding salaries and allowances
of teachers are paid."
</P>
<P>
A new group, the Committee of Concerned Teachers, opposed to
the stand taken by the National Executive saying in a six-point
statement today that "majority of teachers are ready to serve the
nation in conjunction with any government of the day."
</P>
<P>
The statement, signed by Abubakarr Bangura as Chairman and
Moses Konteh as Secretary General, observed that "since 1991 to
date, there has not been an absolute breakdown in the educational
process even though there has never been a stable political
climate."
</P>
<P>
The statement accused the executive of "sending a document to
the Government Treasury to deduct nearly two dollars as Union
dues from teachers salaries nationwide against their wish instead
of the normal one dollar. If this is allowed, we will continue
the strike against the unjustifiable decision of the executive."'
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua, Alpha Timbo, secretary-general of
the Union, rejected the charges saying "We are doing everything
for the good of all teachers."
</P>
<P>
Observers said that although some teachers have been paid up
to June, others are yet to receive salaries and allowances
stretching as far back as March. The military government had
promised to pay all their salaries when it took over in May.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 150,000 school children have been idle since May when
all schools were shut down in the west African state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
