<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Public-Owned Sector Remains Prominent Part Of China's Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The role of publicly-owned
companies has not changed in China's economy, according to a
nation-wide survey on grass-roots companies.
</P>
<P>
It shows that China has 2.62 million enterprises with corporate
status, 1.94 million of which are state or collectively-owned,
making up 73.9 percent of the national economy, and employing 150
million laborers, or 83.8 percent of the number for
corporate-level enterprises.
</P>
<P>
State-owned and collectively-owned capital accounts for 51.1
percent and 21.5 percent, respectively, of the total amount of the
country.
</P>
<P>
The two-year survey showed that the total number of companies
of all kinds with corporate status was 4.4 million at the end of
1996, most of them in industry.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
