<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Forgives Jordan New Amount of Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The United States today forgave
Jordan a new batch of debt valued at 63.4 million U.S. dollars,
Radio Jordan reported.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Ambassador to Jordan Wesley Egan and Jordanian Deputy
Prime Minister and acting Finance Minister Jawad Anani signed here
today an agreement on the debt forgiveness, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
This is the third and also the last agreement between the two
countries to fulfill a U.S. promise to forgive Jordan a debt
totalling 700.4 million dollars. The previous two agreements were
signed respectively in 1994 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
After the signing ceremony, Anani told the press that the debt
forgiveness showed that the U.S. government recognized the
success Jordan had achieved in its monetary and fiscal policies.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed appreciation for the U.S. efforts in debt
forgiveness for Jordan and hoped that Jordan's other creditor
nations would consider such forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
The United States has become a strong financial supporter of
Jordan by granting millions of dollars of aid, forgiving its debt
and helping the kingdom rescheduling of its huge foreign debt
payment.
</P>
<P>
Jordan is one of the main receivers of U.S. aid, along with
Israel and Egypt, in the Mideast. In the past seven years, the
U.S. has provided it with some 1.5 billion dollars in economic and
military aid and debt forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
This year, the U.S. has so far granted an aid of 200 million
dollars to Jordan. And the U.S. Congress is reportedly trying to
increase it to 250 million dollars, despite of its overall plan to
cut down foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that it is the important role of Jordan in
the Mideast peace process and in supporting the U.S. dual
containment policy against Iraq and Iran that prompt the U.S. to
provide Jordan with large amount of aid.
</P>
<P>
Jordan signed a peace treaty and established diplomatic
relations with Israel in 1994, becoming the second of the only two
Arab countries in the Mideast to have signed peace treaties
with Israel after Egypt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
