<DOCNO> XIE19970925.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: HK Showcases Role of Financial Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong has won itself
increased fame as an international financial center by
successfully hosting the World Bank/IMF meetings and visiting
international financiers have become more convinced of its
important role in the global financial sector, commentators said
today.
</P>
<P>
Participants at the September 23-25 W.Bank/IMF annual meetings
agreed there is every reason to believe that Hong Kong's status as
an international financial sector will be ever consolidated and
strengthened.
</P>
<P>
Finance ministers and central bank governors from countries all
over the world gathered in Hong Kong, a Special Administrative
Region (SAR) of China, for the World Bank/International Monetary
Fund (IMF) annual meetings and the relevant seminars which ended
today after a week of lively discussions.
</P>
<P>
The views expressed by the participants reveal the
growing confidence they place in Hong Kong after they have seen
for themselves how the SAR is functioning under the concept of
"one country, two systems."
</P>
<P>
It was the first time for the W.Bank/IMF meetings to take place
in China, and also the first time for them to be hosted by a
financial center. The meetings provided a golden opportunity for
Hong Kong to showcase its excellent achievements and its strong
potential as an international financial center.
</P>
<P>
The meetings coincided with the closing of the 15th National
Congress of the Communist Party of China. The important decision
made at the Congress to press ahead with China's economic
restructuring sent a strong message to participants that China is
wholly committed to creating a socialist market economy and that
as a SAR of China, Hong Kong will surely enjoy an even brighter
future.
</P>
<P>
The meetings took place only two-odd months after Hong Kong's
return to China, participants saw with their own eyes the
post-handover prosperity and stability in this metropolis.
</P>
<P>
As Chinese Premier Li Peng told the opening of the meetings:
"Seeing once is better than hearing one hundred times." What the
participants saw were a prosperous economy, a stable financial
situation and local people's confidence in their future.
</P>
<P>
Both Premier Li Peng and Vice Premier Zhu Rongji stressed time
and again during their stay in Hong Kong that the policy of "one
country, two systems" will be firmly carried out. Chinese finance
officials also explained the significance of one country, two
currencies, two monetary systems and two monetary authorities in
maintaining Hong Kong's status as an international financial
center.
</P>
<P>
IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus' words were widely
representative of the participants: "What better opportunity could
we have to see for ourselves the potential of Hong Kong to become
an even more prosperous place, an even more dynamic center for the
benefit of Southeast Asia within the framework of 'one country,
two systems'?"
</P>
<P>
Over the past few months, while some southeast Asian countries
were hit by the serious financial turbulence, Hong Kong stood
firmly. With a sound financial supervision system and sufficient
foreign reserves, plus proper preventive measures, Hong Kong
calmly defeated speculative attacks and maintained the stability
of its currency.
</P>
<P>
Many participants expressed their appreciation for Hong Kong's
calm handling of the test.
</P>
<P>
Participants noted that Hong Kong's banking system is becoming
mature and increasingly diversified. At present Hong Kong has 182
licensed banks and 62 restricted license banks. In addition, it is
host to more than 360 banks from more than 40 countries, including
some 80 of the world's top 100 banks.
</P>
<P>
Not long ago, Hong Kong gave its support to the IMF's rescue
effort with one billion US dollars to help Thailand, and it also
joined other lending arrangements. Hong Kong is also a member of
both the International Clearing Bank and the World Trade
Organization. All these clearly show Hong Kong's determination and
ability to promote international financial and economic
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Participants also noted that, headed by Tung Chee Hwa, the SAR
government is both pragmatic and efficient in administering Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of Finance Robert Rubin said it is particularly
fitting for the meetings to be held in Hong Kong, a city which has
become such a strong symbol of the dynamism and openness that has
transformed Asia these past three decades.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the presence of the entire international
financial community here speaks to the importance of Hong Kong
sustaining its commitment to hard work in the years to come.
</P>
<P>
Three years ago, when the World Bank and the IMF chose Hong
Kong as the venue for the meetings, many people were still
sceptical about its future. Seeing is believing. Today's Hong Kong
remains prosperous and energetic, and if there is any change, it's
the absence of scepticism.
</P>
<P>
Many World Bank and IMF officials pointed out at the meetings
that the holding of the meetings in Hong Kong and the record
number of participants are themselves a vote of confidence.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is a beautiful and bustling city, said President of
the World Bank James Wolfensohn. It exemplifies the openness,
dynamism and optimism of so much of Asia today, he said.
</P>
<P>
Few would doubt that Hong Kong will continue playing an
important role in the international financial sector.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
