<HEADLINE> Drafting Process of 15th Party Congress Report (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Jiang Zemin, head of the
third generation of leadership of the Communist Party of China
(CPC), delivered a keynote report at the opening session of the
15th CPC National Congress held at he Great Hall of the People on
September 12.
</P>
<P>
The report, titled "Hold High the Great Banner of Deng Xiaoping
Theory for an All-Round Advancement of the Cause of Building
Socialism with Chinese Characteristics to the 21st Century," was
deemed the political declaration of the Communists as they
approach the new century and also the Party's guide to action.
</P>
<P>
The CPC, at its 14th National Congress in 1992, outlined the
principle of building socialism with Chinese characteristics and
determined that the theory was to be the Party's guiding ideology.
</P>
<P>
Soon after the report to the 15th National Congress was
drafted, Jiang and other members of the Standing Committee of the
Political Bureau of the CPC Central Committee announced that the
theme of the congress would be to hold high the great banner of
Deng Xiaoping Theory for an all-round advancement of the cause of
building socialism with Chinese characteristics to the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
The theme was chosen based on the needs of the times and the
people's aspirations.
</P>
<P>
The well-written report has laid a foundation and serves as a
guarantee for the success of the congress held by the CPC at the
turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
While meeting with the writers of the draft report in December
1996, Jiang said the report should focus on this theme, and
expound on the tasks faced by the CPC and the Chinese people at
the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
It should also mobilize all members of the Party and the entire
Chinese people to improve their morale and work with the same
goals in mind, thus attaining the strategic objectives for the
second phase of China's modernization and advancing toward the
third phase, so as to bring a prosperous, democratic and civilized
China into the 21st century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
