<DOCNO> XIE19970925.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: WB/IMF Officials, Bankers Say Bye to HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 25 (Xinhua) -- With a good impression of
Hong Kong, finance officials and bankers from 181 countries said
good-bye to Hong Kong after the doors of the Annual Meetings of
the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund (IMF) closed
here today.
</P>
<P>
Before the closing session of the meetings this morning, World
Bank President James Wolfensohn told reporters: "I have been
coming since 1962. And so far as I can see, there is zero
difference in the way people are conducting themselves today as
against six months ago."
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong returned to China on July 1 after 156 years of
British rule, and has since become a special administrative region
of China under the "one country, two systems" principle.
</P>
<P>
Wolfensohn explained, "It seems to me not because of the
statement of (Chinese Premier) Li Peng but because of what I
observed that there is little or no change either in the pace of
life here or in the way people are operating."
</P>
<P>
"I might also say that the reaction it seems to me of everybody
at the meetings is just to accept the 'one country, two systems'
statement," the World Bank chief said. "So far there does not
appear to be any evidence that things are not going to continue as
they are today."
</P>
<P>
Rogelio Novey, alternate executive director of the
Inter-American Development Bank for Panama and Venezuela, said: "I
am deeply impressed by Hong Kong's wealth, and its modernization."
</P>
<P>
This is the first time for him to come to Hong Kong, he said.
"Hong Kong people are really diligent and efficient. The meeting
is well-organized and the convention center is the best one I have
seen," he commented.
</P>
<P>
Edisor Ortiz-Duran, a banker from Equador, told Xinhua that he
had attended the Annual Meetings of the World Bank-IMF for ten
years "in a row."
</P>
<P>
What impressed him most this year in Hong Kong is that the
entire arrangements for the meetings and their security as well
have been conducted in a smooth and orderly way.
</P>
<P>
During the meetings, Singaporean Finance Minister Richard Hu
said he had seen with his own eyes that Hong Kong remains "exactly
the same" as what it was before the historic handover on July 1
this year.
</P>
<P>
The fact that the meetings were held in Hong Kong is of
symbolic meaning, he pointed out, indicating that the two
international organizations pay great attention to the
Asian-Pacific region and, particularly, to China and its special
administrative region Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"This year's Annual Meetings have set for us, Africans, good
examples -- Asia and, particularly, China," said Frank Douamba,
who comes from Cote d'ivoire and now serves as a representative in
the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
He stressed, "We can learn from you (the Chinese people) how to
accelerate the economic growth and achieve development in
science-technology and culture." He told reporters that he likes
Hong Kong as well.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
