<HEADLINE> Soeharto Asks Civil Servants to Help Fight Fires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto
today instructed all civil servants to help cope and fight the
haze and forest fire disasters.
</P>
<P>
"The president is instructing all civil servants and government
officials in the country to cooperate in the effort to overcome
the disaster," Minister/State Secretary Moerdiono said after
meeting with Soeharto at the Merdeka Palace.
</P>
<P>
Moerdiono said it is urgent that the whole nation should help
deal with the haze and fire disasters as they are already
affecting flight operations and people's daily activities.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Coordinating Minister for the People's Welfare Azwar
Anas said the forest areas that got burned have reached 71,770
hectares in Kalimantan and around 11,562 hectares in Sumatra.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, State Minister for Environment Sarwono Kusumaamadja
said that at least 300,000 hectares of forest have been destroyed
by fires since mid-August.
</P>
<P>
According to officials sources, the Japanese government has
provided assistance worth 430 million rupiah (about 150,000 U.S.
dollars) in the form of 300 pieces of jet shooter equipment,
medicines and masks.
</P>
<P>
The French government has also expressed its intention to send
experts to help Indonesia extinguish the forest fires.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials have also offered assistance to deal with the
forest fires this afternoon, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
Forest fires, which started in mid-August, have now caused
choking smog, which began engulfing areas as distant as the
popular Thai resort of Phuket and the Philippine capital of Manila
a few weeks ago while Malaysia and Singapore have been severely
affected by the haze.
</P>
<P>
The haze has exposed 20 million people to the danger of
respiratory problems in the country as well as in neighboring
countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
