<DOCNO> XIE19970925.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Economic Prospect of African LDCS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The 33 African Least
Developed Countries (LDCS) attained a growth rate of 4.6 percent
Gross Domestic Product (GDP) in 1996, compared to 5.4 percent in
1995, according to "LDCS 1997 Report" just issued here by the
United Nations Conference on Trade and Development (UNCTAD).
</P>
<P>
This is a satisfying performance for Africa's most
impoverished countries for the second consecutive year since
1995.
</P>
<P>
An UNCTAD forecast said, the future is looking decidedly
brighter for these African LDCS. This is because many African
LDCS have experienced higher growth rates since 1994. Nineteen
African LDCS enjoyed growth rates of over 4 percent and 10 other
LDCS enjoyed GDP growth rates higher than 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
There are indications that this trend is set to continue. In
many countries, export production has been increased, inflation
rates have been reduced and reform has been consistently well
implemented since the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
The economic growth in African LDCS has far-reaching
significance for the eradication of poverty both in Africa and
the world as a whole. Of the world's 48 LDCS picked out by the
United Nations organization, 33 are in Africa, which takes up
over 62 percent of all African countries. Therefore, poverty
eradication in the world is directly linked with development of
these African LDCS.
</P>
<P>
The economic performance of African LDCS in 1996 was shaped by
factors of peace and stability prevailing in these countries, the
positive impact of economic reforms, the devaluation of the CFA
Franc and more favourable weather for agriculture, especially in
east and southern Africa. The recovery of the agricultural sector
from drought in 1995 contributed to economic growth in countries
such as Ethiopia, Mozambique and Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Output growth in the nine LDCS which are members of the CFA
Franc zone is estimated to have averaged 4.2 percent in 1996,
lower than the 5 percent for 1995. All the CFA zone LDCS achieved
positive GDP growth in 1996, and all except Chad, Mali and Togo
registered an acceleration of growth rate over the 1995 levels.
</P>
<P>
While outside the CFA zone, the economies of several of the
LDCS which have been consistently implementing economic reforms
for a number of years continued to make progress in 1996, with
growth rates of 4.5 percent or more recorded in Lesotho, Malawi,
Mauritania, Uganda and Tanzania. These countries also improved
their economic performance in terms of export earnings, lower
inflation rates, and consolidated gains made in 1994/95.
</P>
<P>
At present, there are several favourable factors for the
development of African LDCS. First, world prices for tropical
beverages rose steeply in the first half of 1997, and this will
provide a major boost to export earnings, government revenue and
domestic savings in many African LDCS.
</P>
<P>
Second, the good weather which is forecast for 1997 should
allow favourable agricultural harvests.
</P>
<P>
Third, the economic recovery in many of the African LDCS, as a
result of the sustained implementation of economic reforms, has
begun to gain some momentum over the last two years.
</P>
<P>
Fourth, the commitment to reforms which governments in the
region have demonstrated should enhance confidence among private
sector business and provide a stimulus to investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970925.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian FM to Visit Allies, Business Partners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Australian Foreign Minister
Alexander Downer is to visit Australia's allies the United States
and Japan and its important regional business partners -- the
Republic of Korea, Hong Kong and the Philippines in the next few
weeks.
</P>
<P>
Downer announced here today that he will talk with his U.S.
counterpart, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, and Secretary
of Defense William Cohen on October 8 in Washington as part of the
annual Australia-U.S. Ministerial Consultations on a wide-range of
issues.
</P>
<P>
They will exchange views on priority issues such as the U.S.
and Australia's relations with East Asia, bilateral defense
relationship and a range of issues on the global agenda, Downer
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"This year's consultations will continue with the positive
momentum in the Australian-U.S. relationship which was generated
from last year's successful consultations," the foreign minister
said.
</P>
<P>
Australia strengthened its military cooperation with the United
States last year as part of the major policy adjustment by the
government of John Howard, which took office in March 1996.
</P>
<P>
Downer said the forthcoming consultations would be "timely" as
they will begin shortly after high-level U.S.-Japan consultations
and precede a U.S.-Chinese summit.
</P>
<P>
"I will undertake my first bilateral visit to the Philippines
on October 10-12, as a demonstration of my strong commitment to
strengthening the relationship," Downer said.
</P>
<P>
"On October 13 I will be taking part in the Japan-South Pacific
Forum Leaders Summit in Tokyo," the foreign minister said.
</P>
<P>
The summit will focus on the economic circumstances of Pacific
island countries and opportunities and challenges for development
cooperation and assistance, he said.
</P>
<P>
"I have been invited by the World Economic Forum to deliver a
keynote speech at this year's East Asia Economic Summit in Hong
Kong on October 15," Downer added.
</P>
<P>
As his last leg of the tour, Downer will pay a visit to the
Republic of Korea (ROK) on October 16-17, which "underlines the
priority the (Australian) government attaches to close bilateral
cooperation with ROK," Australia's second largest market, fourth
largest trading partner and a growing source of foreign
investment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
