<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The 52nd Annual Meetings of
the World Bank and International Monetary Fund (IMF) were fruitful
and important for prioritizing the future work of the two
international financial institutions, a senior Chinese official
said here today.
</P>
<P>
Good progress was made in some major issues at the three-day
World Bank/IMF meetings which ended in Hong Kong earlier today,
Chinese Vice-Finance Minister Liu Jibin told Xinhua in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
The achievements of the meetings are important for setting
priority of the future work of the World Bank and the IMF and for
the growth of the global economy and international financing, Liu
said.
</P>
<P>
In their speeches made at the opening of the World Bank/IMF
meetings and a series of seminars prior to the meetings
respectively, Premier Li Peng and Vice-Premier Zhu Rongji briefed
the audience on the brilliant achievements China has scored in its
reform and opening-up as well as the major policies decided at the
just-ended 15th National Congress of the Communist Party of China,
Liu said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese leaders also reiterated China's determination to
implement the principle of "one country, two systems" in Hong Kong
and maintain its prosperity and stability.
</P>
<P>
The six propositions Premier Li expounded in his speech
reflected the aspirations of the developing countries and won wide
acclaim from representatives of the developing world at the
meetings, Liu said.
</P>
<P>
Participants at the meetings discussed in detail the current
international economic situation and reached some consensus, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Expressing grave concern about the recent currency turmoil in
Southeast Asia, they believed that the effects of the financial
turbulence could be tapering off if vigorous measures are taken
and bilateral and multilateral international cooperation is
conducted on the basis of drawing lessons from the event, Liu
said.
</P>
<P>
The participants were all optimistic about Asia's economic
growth in the future, he said.
</P>
<P>
Important decisions were made at the meetings on the policies
of the World Bank and the IMF. Agreement was reached on an
increase in the quota of the Multilateral Investment Guarantee
Agency (MIGA) and on the distribution of the 21.4 billion Special
Drawing Rights (SDR)of the IMF.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of implementing the Heavily Indebted Poor
Countries (HIPC) Initiative, members of the Paris Club agreed to
speed up the process of reducing these countries' debts.
</P>
<P>
China, as a creditor nation, also promised to actively get
involved in this initiative, Liu said.
</P>
<P>
The annual meetings also made headway in the fields of
promoting international capital flows and enhancing financial
surveillance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
