<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Press Watchdog Unveils Guidelines on Privacy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Britain's press watchdog the
Press Complaints Commission (PCC) today unveiled a series of new
tough privacy guidelines for the newspaper industry in the wake of
the death of Diana, Princess of Wales.
</P>
<P>
The guidelines were drawn up as part of an urgent review of the
industry's Code of Practice, which began on September 1 just one
day after the death of Diana in a car accident, allegedly caused
by chasing photographers known as Paparazzi.
</P>
<P>
Culture, Media and Sport Secretary Chris Smith welcomed the
guidelines, the main points of which are:
</P>
<P>
Banning publication of pictures obtained illegally or through
"persistent pursuit."
</P>
<P>
Placing editors under obligation to check how pictures were
obtained.
</P>
<P>
Introducing measures to prevent so-called media scrums and
collective harassment.
</P>
<P>
Introducing new guidelines specifically for the children of
figures in the public eye, such as Princes William and Harry.
</P>
<P>
Widening the definition of private property on which individual
can expect not to be photographed.
</P>
<P>
However, Roger Gale, a Conservative MP, warned that the
proposals would have to be backed up by strict sanctions and fines
if they were to have any effect. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
