<HEADLINE> China's Largest Ecological Pilot Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Work on a 1,922-sq.km. area
in southwest China's Sichuan province that is China's largest
ecological pilot zone started today.
</P>
<P>
It is expected to cost 3.1 billion yuan and to be completed by
the end of the year 2009.
</P>
<P>
The pilot zone is one of 69 decided by the State Bureau of
Environmental Protection last year. There are 38 pilot projects in
ecological agriculture, ecological industry, vegetation coverage,
and endangered species protection in the zone.
</P>
<P>
Work has started on rare flower and plant, pig raising,
vegetable growing, and non-polluting manufacturing projects.
</P>
<P>
The ecologic pilot zone is located on the Chengdu Plain, a
major agricultural base with the world's oldest water conservation
work, the Dujiangyan project.  
</P>
</TEXT>
