<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey bomb Kurdish rebel camps in Northern Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Turkish fighter-bombers today
carried out a bombing strike on suspected Kurdish rebel camps in
northern Iraq, the semi-official Anatolia news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Bombs were unleashed on 15 rebel camps, near the Iranian and
Syrian borders, where some 1,000 Kurdish militants recently
converged from Iran and Syria, the report said.
</P>
<P>
There was no immediate report of casualties of the militants.
</P>
<P>
The rebels of the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party, which has
been fighting a 13-year-old separatist war, use the area as a
springboard to launch attacks into Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted high-ranking Turkish military sources, who
declined to be named, as saying the bombing was aimed at blocking
them from infiltrating into Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Some 8,000 Turkish troops, backed by about 130 tanks, have
entered northern Iraq in a cross-border operation against the
rebels. The General Staff of the Turkish military confirmed this
move but refused to check the numbers.
</P>
<P>
The sources stressed that the recent attacks were not a
large-scale military operation like the one in May.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Turkish Foreign Ministry spokesman Sermet Atacanli
confirmed today's attack, describing it as "routine and limited."
The government troops can take such an action if they think it
necessary, he said.
</P>
<P>
Last May Turkey sent as many as 50,000 troops, backed by
hundreds of tanks and heavy artillery, into northern Iraq to wipe
out rebel camps, triggering strong criticism from Iran and
neighboring Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
In mid-June, the military began withdrawal but a portion of
troops apparently have remained there.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, Iraq called on Turkey to immediately withdraw
its troops from northern Iraq and stop military invasion into
Iraq's territory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
