<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moon Created From Collision: New Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The moon was created from the
debris of a collision between the earth and an object three times
the size of Mars billions of years ago, according to a latest
study.
</P>
<P>
The science journal Nature published today quoted researchers
from the University of Colorado and the Tokyo University as saying
that the huge object might have crashed into the earth with a
force that caused its entire crust to melt and wiped out portions
of its mantle.
</P>
<P>
The scientists used computers to simulate the results of a
variety of impacts by rogue protoplanets early in the earth's
history.
</P>
<P>
The scientists made the discovery while testing a solution to
the great puzzle of the origins of the moon -- the "great impactor
theory." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970925.0121 </DOCNO>
