<HEADLINE> Strong Sino-U.S. Ties Conducive to Global Prosperity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 25 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Treasury Secretary
Robert Rubin said here today that building strong
Sino-U.S. relations is crucial to global prosperity and stability.
</P>
<P>
Rubin made the statement in his speech "Sino-U.S. Intertests
and Global Economics" presented to 200 students and teachers at
the Chinese People's University.
</P>
<P>
"China, the largest developing nation on earth, and the United
States, the largest industrialized nation, stand at the forefront
worldwide," said Rubin. He went on to say that the two nations
will have the two largest economies on earth in the not too
distant future, a fact which makes it absolutely essential to
build strong relations to ensure global prosperity and stability.
</P>
<P>
"People in the United States have enormous interest in seeing a
successful China. Our economies are becoming more closely linked
as China becomes more integrated into the global economy and we
should work together on wide-ranging fronts," said Rubin.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang Zemin's report to the recent 15th National
Congress emphasized greater openness and integration into the
global economy, said Rubin, adding that this will require opening
markets to trade and investment, and greater participation in
international organizations, China has been much more active in
such organizations over the past few years and is currently playing
an important role in the IMF, World Bank and APEC.
</P>
<P>
Rubin attended the 52nd Annual Meetings of the World Bank and
the International Monetary Fund prior to beginning his first visit
to China as U.S. Treasury Secretary. He is visiting China at
the invitation of the Ministry of Finance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
