<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Firmer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
surrendered early gains to close only slightly firmer, with the
woes of food ingredient company Burns Philp &AMP; Co a focus.
</P>
<P>
Brokers said afternoon profit-taking pulled the local bourse
off its highs, with some individual stocks impacted by today's
options expiry.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index ended 10.3 points firmer at a new
record close of 2779.2 having earlier touched 2797.3.
</P>
<P>
Investors greeted Burns Philp's decision to slash 504 million
U.S. dollars from the book value of its North American and
European herb and spice businesses last night by wiping almost the
same amount from its market capitalization.
</P>
<P>
Burns Philp's shares plummeted 1.26 Australian dollars to 90
cents on second highest market volume of 12.39 million shares.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index ended 14.9 points firmer at 4610.9
while the all resources gained seven to 1333.2.
</P>
<P>
Resources giant BHP added eight cents to 15.81 Australian
dollars while mining company Rio Tinto shed 8.5 cents to 20.685
Australian dollars, WMC lifted 14.5 cents to 6.245 Australian
dollars and Pasminco fell 11 cents to 2.33 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Media giant News Corp followed up a strong night's trading in
New York with a 2.6 percent rise in its ordinary shares in Sydney,
closing 18 cents up at 7.01 Australian dollars. Its preferred
shares gained 17.8 cents, or 3.04 percent, to 6.03 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Property and financial services group Lend Lease lost 80.9
cents to 32.95 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Coca-Cola Amatil rose 26.6 cents to 15.41 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index closed 18.2 points higher at 1254.1, with gold
bullion in Sydney closing at 323.30 U.S. dollars an ounce compared
to 322.30 U.S. dollars at yesterday's close in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
National turnover totaled 433.37 million shares valued at 1.18
billion Australian dollars (849.6 million U.S. dollars), with
rising issues beating falls by 633 to 530. 
</P>
