<HEADLINE> Britain Expects Too Low Children's Mathematics Ability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The British government's
expectations of children's mathematics abilities may be too low,
said a report published Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report, launched by Chris Woodhead, chief inspector of
schools, found too little attention being given to children's
mental arithmetic ability.
</P>
<P>
In a school surveyed, only one pupil per class in the
seven-year-old grade could write down a two-digit number expressed
in words, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Woodhead said primary schools had to aim above the present
national targets if sufficient improvement were to be made.
</P>
<P>
He also urged the government to keep the standard of national
tests under review.
</P>
<P>
"If we are not expecting enough in the tests, then clearly we
are not stretching children enough and aren't going to make up the
gap with our international competitors." he said.
</P>
<P>
England and Scotland were in the bottom third of the 42
countries taking part in the latest international survey of
mathematics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
