<HEADLINE> Pakistan, India to Resume Dialogue in Months: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan and India will
resume bilateral dialogue in a few months, a Foreign Office
spokesman said here today.
</P>
<P>
"Let us hope that India responds positively to the constructive
approach that Pakistan has adopted," said the spokesman at a
weekly briefing while responding to questions about the future of
Indo-Pak talks after the inconclusive third round held in New
Delhi last week.
</P>
<P>
He said Pakistan reiterated its commitment to continue the
talks and prime ministers of Pakistan and India had agreed on
Tuesday for a continuation of the process in their meeting in New
York, where they were attending the UN General Assembly session.
</P>
<P>
However, said the spokesman, "we must underline that Kashmir
has a fundamental place in the talks and it cannot be relegated to
a lower place."
</P>
<P>
He said that a methodology had to be agreed upon how to take up
different issues during the course of negotiations between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the reaction by Indian leadership regarding a
"no-war pact" between the two countries, the spokesman said "we
are very surprised that Indian Prime Minister Inder Kumar Gujral
did not react to the host of proposals of Pakistani Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif."
</P>
<P>
"These were positive proposals, but Gujral did not make any
reference to them during his meeting with Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif, " the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
However, "We remain committed to the broad range of dialogue in
a positive spirit, " he said, adding that the proposals would be
raised under appropriate items under the agenda for talks.
</P>
<P>
About India's efforts for getting a seat in the UN Security
Council, the spokesman said that India was pursuing a
"universalistic approach" in this matter.
</P>
<P>
He said that India has not implemented the United Nations
resolutions which have been accepted by India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
"A respect for the UN charter and resolutions should be
considered fundamental for those seeking permanent membership of
the United Nations Security Council," the spokesman said.
</P>
