<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa, Lesotho Complete First Phase of Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Residents in South
Africa's Gauteng Province could soon have an alternate source of
water supply as a dam in Lesotho began to gush its first liters
to the province on Wednesday, "The Star" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The release of the water marked the completion of the first
phase of the Lesotho Highlands Water project, a 19-billion-Rand
joint venture between South Africa and Lesotho.
</P>
<P>
The project was supposed to build two dams in Lesotho to
supply water to South African households and industries and at
the same time generate electricity for Lesotho.
</P>
<P>
However, the future of the follow-up phases of the project
still hangs in the scale as the South African side is reluctant
to go ahead with it.
</P>
<P>
While jubilation flowed among thousands of villagers when the
sluice gates were opened, South African officials were notably
absent.
</P>
<P>
Adults in their Sunday best and children in school uniforms
stood for hours on hilltops to wait for the opening of the
sluices, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
South African Water Affairs Minister Kader Asmal has said that
his country was committed only to the first phase of the project
and that future decisions would be made only after all water
resources had been researched, The Star said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
