<DOCNO> XIE19970925.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Call for Wide Use of Nicotine Replacement Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Tobacco control experts
Wednesday called on countries "to allow proven nicotine
replacement products to be more widely available through
relaxation of regulations governing the use of these products."
</P>
<P>
At the end of a three-day roundtable meeting, the experts,
including doctors, lawyers and sociologists, adopted a series of
economic and legal policy recommendations aimed at reducing the
human toll caused by smoking.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that the existing smoking control policies focus
on prevention and cessation, but more attention is needed on
smoking reduction through alternative nicotine delivery systems
(ANDS).
</P>
<P>
They suggested new strategies which allow addicted smokers
access to safe nicotine products.
</P>
<P>
They also called for a comprehensive nicotine regulatory
approach that "gives the greatest relative advantage to the least
harmful products."
</P>
<P>
The meeting was held under the auspices of the United Nations
Focal Point on Tobacco or Health based at the U.N. Conference on
Trade and Development (UNCTAD). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970925.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sessional Paper on AIDS Passed at Kenyan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The National Assembly of
Kenya has passed a Sessional Paper No. 4 of 1997 on AIDS in a bid
to help the government formulate strategies to curb the spread of
the disease over the next 15 years and beyond.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Nation today reported that the paper, among other
things, recommended that anyone wilfully infects another with the
deadly virus be held guilty of man-slaughter.
</P>
<P>
During the debate on the paper, two members of parliament
proposed that the AIDS scourge be declared a national disaster,
enabling the government to allocate more resources to combat the
disease.
</P>
<P>
Health Assistant Minister Basil Criticos told the parliament
that the government was determined to stop the spread of AIDS but
was constrained by slow attitude and behavior change toward
casual sex by the public.
</P>
<P>
He dismissed calls for isolation of AIDS victims, saying it
would not be possible to round up all the infected people.
</P>
<P>
Alego-Usonga MP Otieno Mak'Onyango asked the government to set
up an AIDS Control Fund to help minimize the spread of the
disease and support its victims.
</P>
<P>
He also called for the elevation of the AIDS research unit,
currently under Kenya Medical Research Institute, to a
fully-fledged body.
</P>
<P>
Karachuonyo MP Phoebe Asiyo appealed to the government to
subsidize drugs for complications arising from AIDS.
</P>
<P>
The disease has already killed 230,000 Kenyans aged between 15
and 39 years and the AIDS deaths will rise to one million by the
year 2000 in the country with a population of 28 million.
</P>
<P>
According to an estimate by the Regional Director of the Aids
Control and Prevention Project, more than 1.7 million Kenyans
might be infected with the AIDS virus by the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
The 1996 World Population Data Sheet has ranked Kenya among 30
countries in the world whose future population projections will
be affected adversely by the HIV/AIDS scourge. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
