<HEADLINE> Three Mine-workers Injured in Earthquake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Three mine workers from
the East Driefontein Gold Mine were injured when a fairly strong
earthquake rocked the area in the small hours this morning, the
South African Press Association (SAPA) said today.
</P>
<P>
The effect of the tremor, measured at 4.2 on the Richter
scale, was felt in Johannesburg, more than 50 kilometers away
from the epicenter.
</P>
<P>
The three miners suffered head, leg and back injuries, but
they were in a stable condition at the Leslie Williams Mine
Hospital, SAPA quoted mine management spokesman Andrew Davidson
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The mine dismissed speculations that deep level mining had
caused the quake.
</P>
<P>
"The seismic monitoring station at West Driefontein determined
the epicenter at 3,300 meters below surface, which is almost a
kilometer below the deepest level workings of East Driefontein,"
Davidson said.
</P>
<P>
The injured were working 2,300 meters below ground level near
the mine's No. 4 sub-vertical shaft.
</P>
<P>
"A full investigation into the effects of the seismic incident
will take place. Damage was caused to the shaft and underground
installations, but possible production losses cannot be
quantified at this stage," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
No employees were missing as a result of the incident, the
report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
