<HEADLINE> Iraq Demands Turkish Troop Pullback from North </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Iraq today called on Turkey
to immediately withdraw its troops from northern Iraq and prevent
from repeating aggression of Iraqi territory.
</P>
<P>
A Foreign Ministry spokesman said the Iraqi government rejects
absolutely Turkey's excuse to defend its invasion of northern
Iraq, which run against international laws as well as the United
Nations charter.
</P>
<P>
"Pursuit of the rebels can not be the excuse for Turkey's
violation of Iraq's territorial integrity," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
This new aggression contradicts totally Turkey's earlier claims
that it adheres to the principle of respecting the sovereignty of
Iraqi territory, he added.
</P>
<P>
About 7,000 Turkish troops backed by more than 100 tanks
crossed into northern Iraq on September 22 to join the Turkish
forces there.
</P>
<P>
They were reinforcing in the attack on Turkey's fugitive
militants of the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party, which has been
fighting for an independent Kurdish state in southeastern Turkey
since 13 years ago.
</P>
<P>
On May 14, some 50,000 Turkish troops entered northern Iraq in
a cross-border military operation against the Kurdish rebels.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish military said on June 19 that it had pull out most
of its forces from northern Iraq, but never announced a complete
withdrawal from the area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
