<HEADLINE> S. Africa Mulls Privatization of SA Airways </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 25 (Xinhua) -- An interministerial
cabinet committee will decide on the process of privatizing South
African Airways (SAA) next month, the "Business Day" newspaper
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted a spokesman for Public Enterprises Minister
Stella Sigcau as saying on Wednesday that no decision has been
made on the percentage stake for sale, but the committee will
decide on October 16.
</P>
<P>
However, Saki Macozoma, managing director of SAA's state-owned
parent group Transnet, said in London on Tuesday that the South
African government will probably sell 25 to 30 percent of SAA to
a strategic equity partner.
</P>
<P>
Several carriers have expressed interest in acquiring a stake
in SAA, including British Airway, Deutsche Lufthansa and Virgin
Atlantic, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Macozoma said the restructuring of the national flag carrier
is a priority as the country's privatization drive moves into the
transport sector.
</P>
<P>
He said Transnet and SAA are looking for a privatization
adviser for the sale, which might be completed next year. In the
interim, they have been using HSBC, the overall adviser on
restructuring state assets.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's privatization program, often attacked as too
slow, has picked up speed this year following the sale of a 30
percent stake in a telecom company, Telkom, to a U.S.-Malaysian
consortium.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the government sold 100 percent of a small
regional carrier, Sun Air, to a local consortium.
</P>
<P>
Plans are also advanced for the part privatization of the
Airports Company which operates Africa's busiest airport in
Johannesburg, along with airports in Cape Town and Durban and six
regional airports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
