<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 30 Million Nigerians May Go Blind: UNICEF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Some 30 million Nigerians are
at the risk of being blind unless onchocerciasis or river
blindness is effectively controlled, according to the United
Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF).
</P>
<P>
About 10 million Nigerians are already afflicted with the
disease with 15,000 blind as a result, the New Nigerian reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The official newspaper quoted UNICEF Project Officer Emmanuel
Gemade as saying that river blindness is a major cause of severe
blindness in northern Nigeria, while the southern population are
faced with the problem of skin impairment.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF has received 4.6 million ivermectin tablets valued at
16.8 million U.S. Dollars for the control of the disease which it
has used to treat 2.7 million people.
</P>
<P>
The organization needs 1.9 million Dollars to push the
onchocerciasis control program in Nigeria to its peak by 1999
when foreign funding is expected to ease, Gemade said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, 17.6 million people the world over are
afflicted with river blindness and Africa has 99 percent of the
figure.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, 825,000 are children and 20 percent of them has
visual impairments of various degrees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
