<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian Forex Rating Outlook Downgraded to Negative </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 25 (Xinhua) -- A leading credit rating
agency today downgraded Malaysia's long-term foreign currency
rating outlook from "stable" to "negative," dealing a fresh blow
to confidence in the economy.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-based Standard &AMP; Poor's said in a statement issued
here today that the negative outlook is based on the growing
possibility of a downgrade. It said the country's rapid credit
growth was "financing an unsustainable boom in investment," now at
more than 40 percent of the gross domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
The agency said that with the economy operating at capacity, it
would put pressure on the inflationary level.
</P>
<P>
It forecast Malaysia's current account deficit to exceed 6
percent of the GDP this year.
</P>
<P>
According to the rating agency, there was also likelihood that
bank asset quality would deteriorate significantly next year.
</P>
<P>
Apart from that, total credit to the private sector and public
enterprises -- a leading indicator of asset-quality problems -
will exceed 170 percent of the GDP in 1997, indicating very high
private-sector leverage, it added.
</P>
<P>
It warned that in particular, the financial sector's exposure
to the property market underscores the system's vulnerability to
slowing economic growth, adding that potentially large loan losses
in the financial sector would weaken the government's financial
position as well as the economy's medium-term growth prospects.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's future rating hinges on effective steps, starting
with the 1998 budget proposal to be presented in October, to slow
excessive demand, it said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
