<HEADLINE> International Groups Urged to Help Put out Forest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia today urged
international environmental groups to come forward to help put out
the forest fires in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Primary Industries Minister Lim Keng Yaik said today
this was the time for the groups who have been vocal about forest
conservation to prove that they really love the environment.
</P>
<P>
If they do not respond it will show that they have vested
interests when they cry out for preserving the environment, he
told reporters here after opening a workshop for companies
investing in the forestry sector abroad.
</P>
<P>
The minister said so far not a single environmental group had
come forward to help douse the fires which have been alleged the
main cause for the current haze in this region.
</P>
<P>
The fires got out of control in Sumatra and kalimantan due to
the current dry climate and non-enforcement of the laws relating
to open burning by the Indonesian authorities, Lim said.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has been seriously affected by the haze with the air
quality for the whole country having deteriorated.
</P>
<P>
In Sarawak where a state of haze emergency was declared a week
ago, the Air Pollutant Index in the state capital Kuching today
remained at the hazardous level, according to a statement by the
Department of Environment.
</P>
<P>
The air quality in 14 other areas including Kuala Lumpur today
remained at the unhealthy level.  
</P>
</TEXT>
