<HEADLINE> Israel Wants No Change of Joint Exercises Date </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Israel does not want a change
of the date of the planned mid-November joint naval exercises with
the United States and Turkey, an Israeli embassy spokesman said
here today.
</P>
<P>
Nissan Amdor told Xinhua on telephone that the three sides are
trying to fix a final date for the military exercises which had
been projected in eastern Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
Local English newspaper Turkish Daily News today quoted
U.S. military sources in Pentagon as saying that the planned
Israeli-Turkish-U.S. joint naval exercises had been postponed
until next January.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that the reason behind the delay was that
another joint military exercises between the United States and
Israel would be held at the same time and the same area.
</P>
<P>
Admitting that Israel has received such reports, Amdor said
that the Israeli government has never asked for a postponement of
the three-way war games.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone interview with Xinhua, a senior official from
the Turkish Foreign Ministry, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said that they have not reached any official consensus
on the postponement yet.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Foreign Ministry has not made any statements
regarding the issue so far, he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Embassy here was not available for comment.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Turkish-U.S. joint naval war games were scheduled
to be held on November 16 off the Israeli coast in the eastern
Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
The planned maneuvers had prompted severe criticism from some
Arab nations, which accused Turkey, a Muslim-dominant country, of
betraying the interests of the Muslim world by siding with the
Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish government, however, has been trying to placate its
Arab neighbors by assuring them the exercises are not directed
against any other country but merely "a search-and-rescue
operation" devoid of any strategic importance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
