<DOCNO> XIE19970925.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Hospitals Directed to be Prepared </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Health Secretary
Carmencita Reodica today directed all hospitals in the country to
be well prepared for possible cases as aftermath of the haze
brought about by the forest fire in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The haze, expected to worsen air pollution particularly in
Metro Manila, has covered southern and western Philippines
including Palawan, Zamboanga, Davao, General Santos and other
parts of Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
Hospitals and health offices should have enough stocks of
oxygen and bronchodilators to meet the demands of increasing
incidence of upper respiratory tract infection, Reodica said.
</P>
<P>
They were also told to monitor and report to the office of the
Health Secretary any unusual increase in the number of the said
ailments.
</P>
<P>
The health chief also directed hospitals and offices to conduct
information campaign as to how the public avoid the health hazard
of the haze especially the high risk individuals such as the very
young, elderly and asthmatics.
</P>
<P>
Reodica earlier asked the people living in areas severely
affected by smoke haze to stay indoors as much as possible and to
wear dust masks or wet cloth when necessary or when going outside
the house.
</P>
<P>
Motorists are also told to exercise extreme caution whenever on
the road to prevent accidents.
</P>
<P>
President Ramos Wednesday mobilized government agencies to deal
with the haze and offered the Philippines' help for its more
seriously affected Southeast Asian neighbors.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Environment and Natural Resources said the
haze could affect Metro Manila in two days. The sky in Manila was
generally overcast in recent days.  
</P>
</TEXT>
