<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Gorges Canal Meets Requirements of Water Flow, Navigation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YICHANG, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The open-cut canal built near
the Three Gorges after damming of the main stream of Yangtze River
has met requirements for water flow and navigation, according to
local sources.
</P>
<P>
Beginning on October 1, all ships will sail on the man-made
canal instead of the main river course of the Yangtze.
</P>
<P>
China plans to cut off the main stream of the Yangtze from
early November to construct a gigantic water control dam at the
Three Gorges site, located on the middle reaches of the
Yangtze. An open-cut canal and a temporary ship lock have been
built to facilitate smooth navigation on Yangtze.
</P>
<P>
Situated on the southern bank of the river, the canal is 3,726
m long, 350 m wide at the bed and 58 m deep. Both its width and
height exceed the famed Suez and Panama canals, according to
experts.
</P>
<P>
Ships will be able to sail safely on the canal when water flow
speed falls within 20,000 cu m per second. Under this condition,
the canal, which was filled with water on May 1, will be open for
safe navigation for an average of 272 days in a year.
</P>
<P>
The temporary ship lock and lift attached to the northern bank
of the Yangtze will be put into service for five months of the
year when flood season begins and the water flow speed is higher
than 20,000 cu m per second.
</P>
<P>
The ship lock, which is capable of hauling a fleet with 3,000
DWT (dead weight tonnages) at a time, is now under construction
and will be operational next April. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
