<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Progress in Angolan Peace Process Falls Short of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Although progress has been
made in the peace process of Angola since August, it has not met
the U.N. requirements, U.N. special envoy based in Angola Blondin
Beye said.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks to reporters after his talks with Angolan
President Eduardo dos Santos Wednesday, during which the two
sides discussed the implementation of the Lusaka Peace Agreement
in the country.
</P>
<P>
The U. N. Security Council decided to impose sanctions on the
opposition National Union for the Total Independence of Angola
(UNITA) if it does not fully observe the peace agreement signed
in 1994 and complete all the tasks under the agreement by the end
of September.
</P>
<P>
Beye urged the two parties of the agreement to take a positive
attitude to maintain the new atmosphere emerging in the peace
process recently as the deadline is drawing nearer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
