<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Offers To Help Fight Indonesian Fires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Australia today offered to
help Indonesia tackle its disastrous forest fires which have
blanketed much of Southeast Asia in a thick haze.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Alexander Downer told the Australian
Parliament that he had instructed Australia's Ambassador in
Jakarta John McCarthy to make a detailed assessment of the
situation and report on the kinds of help Australia could deliver.
</P>
<P>
"We will then having undertaken that task, respond with
appropriate assistance to the Indonesian Government to help deal
with this extremely difficult problem which has afflicted people
throughout Southeast Asia," he said.
</P>
<P>
Firefighters from Victoria are on stand-by to fly to the region
to help combat the crisis for what would be their first overseas
assignment, and New South Wales Government has also offered
assistance, reports said.
</P>
<P>
Smoke from fires in Borneo (in Kalimantan island) and Sumatra,
has cast a pall over all three countries of Indonesia, Malaysia
and Singapore for months and dramatically worsened air pollution,
according to reports.
</P>
<P>
The smog has also spread to the Philippines and the Southern
Thailand resort island of Phuket. The Australian government has
warned people to consider deferring plans to travel to the region.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
