<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 08:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Envoy: Oslo Dream Turning Into Nightmare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The outgoing U.S.
Ambassador to Israel Martin Indyk said that the Oslo peace process
which began four years now seems to be turning into a nightmare.
</P>
<P>
According to local newspapers today, Indyk, addressing the
Israeli Council for Peace and Security here Wednesday, said "it
is clear to all of us that something is fundamentally wrong here."
</P>
<P>
He said the peace process has deeply disappointed both Israel
and the Palestinian National Authority (PNA), adding unilateral
actions taken by the Israeli government and the terror attacks
against Israelis are the reasons.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time of the U.S. envoy to openly criticize
the Israeli government for harming the Oslo peace process. His
remarks make big headline stories in local newspapers today.
</P>
<P>
Indyk said to blame for the current crisis of the Middle East
peace process was not the issue, but rather "how to get out of
this mess." He called on both Israel and PNA to abandon a
"zero-sum game mentality" in which one side's loss is the other
side's gain.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright's
urging for PNA President Yasser Arafat to make "100 percent
effort" in fighting terror, and pledged continued American support
for the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
