<HEADLINE> Two Overseas Banks Opens Branches in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 25 (Xinhua) -- China's central bank has
approved the opening in Beijing of branches of two more overseas
banks, the National Bank of Paris, and the Development Bank of
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
The People's Bank of China approved the applications of the two
banks to upgrade their representative offices into branch banks in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
So far, Beijing has branches of 13 overseas banks from 10
countries and regions, including Citibank from the US, Hong Kong
and Shanghai Banking Corporation, and Japan's Mitsubishi Bank.
</P>
<P>
Ten are now operating in Beijing, and their businesses are
running well, according to bank officials.
</P>
<P>
The National Bank of Paris, which opened its Beijing office in
1980, is the first European bank to establish a branch in the
Chinese capital. It has helped raising funds for many
infrastructure projects in China.
</P>
<P>
The Development Bank of Singapore, that country's biggest
commercial bank, has also been successfully involved in
construction of China's power plants, telecommunications and
infrastructure facilities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
