<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Promises To Bolster Settlements In West </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu said last night that his government will
continue to bolster the Jewish settlement in the west bank,
Israeli Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a ceremony marking the 30th anniversary of the
renewal of Jewish settlements last night in Gush Etzion, south of
Jerusalem, Netanyahu said that his government plans to build an
additional 300 housing units for Jewish Settlers in Efrat, near
Gush Etzion.
</P>
<P>
He said the area of Gush Etzion and Efrat is an inseparable
part of Jerusalem and Israel.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's announcement of the new housing settlement plan in
the West Bank was really a surprise to all and will surely cause
more confrontation between Israel and the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
The Israeli Radio today quoted U.S. State Department spokesman
James Rubin as saying that U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright does not regard this plan as consistent with that kind
of climate for negotiations in the Middle East that she hopes
to create.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said that Netanyahu even did not mention that plan
during his telephone call early in the day with Albright and she
wanted to see the details before making a final decision.
</P>
<P>
Albright made a mediation trip to the region earlier this month
in a bid to revive the deadlocked Middle East peace process. But
she failed to persuade the Israelis to stop building Jewish
settlements in Arab East Jerusalem. Palestinian-Israeli peace
talks stalled in March when Israeli government began building Har
Homa settlement which sparked Palestinian and Arab protests and
violence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
