<HEADLINE> Thai Foreign Minister Says ASEAN Backs Hun Sen at U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The Association of Southeast
Asian Nations (ASEAN) has given its support for Cambodian Co-Prime
Ministers Ung Huot and Hun Sen at the United Nations General
Assembly in New York, local reports said today.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile ASEAN foreign ministers in New York plan to meet
ousted Co-Prime Minister Prince Norodom Ranariddh, who claimed the
vacant seat for Cambodia at the U.N. General Assembly, the Bangkok
Post quoted Thai Foreign Minister Prachuab Chaiyasarn as saying.
</P>
<P>
The decisions were made as ASEAN foreign ministers met on the
sidelines of the 52nd U.N. General Assembly session in New York to
discuss the Cambodia issue, Prachuab told the newspaper in a
telephone interview from overseas.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN's support for Hun Sen and Ung Huot was promoted by
Cambodian King Norodom Sihanouk's approval for them to represent
the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, the final decision will rest with the U.N.
credentials committee, which is expected to meet before the
current session ends in December.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia's seat at the U.N. assembly has been left vacant since
the United States launched a bid to block the participation of Hun
Sen who ousted Ranariddh two months ago.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN ministers will hold separate talks with Ung Huot and
Ranariddh to reiterate requests for a military ceasefire in
Cambodia as well as cooperation in preparing for the elections
scheduled for May 1998. 
</P>
