<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0730 GMT, September 25 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA -- The main opposition Bangladesh Nationalist Party
(BNP) today observed a dawn-to-dusk general strike across the
country in protest against government repression on political
rivals and ban on street rallies and processions.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Monday, the opposition on the same plea enforced a
12-hour general strike in the capital of Dhaka, which was observed
peacefully barring some stray incidents. (Bangladesh-Strike)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HONG KONG -- The 52nd Annual Meetings of the World Bank and
the International Monetary Fund (IMF) closed here today, with
good organization work of the Chinese government and the
authorities of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(HKSAR) highly appreciated.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the closing session, World Bank President James
Wolfensohn first thanked China and the HKSAR for the environment
and hospitality they have provided. (HK-WB/IMF Meetings-Close)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- The Indo-Pak Friendship Association has expressed
happiness that a meeting between Prime Minister Inder Kumar Gujral
and his Pak counterpart Nawaz Sharif in New York on Tuesday has
resulted in a positive gain.
</P>
<P>
The spirit that guided the prime ministers of India and
Pakistan to initiate closer ties and improve neighborly relations
has been well maintained and is moving in right direction,
according to the forum's secretariat sources here
today. (India-Pakistan-Relations)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- At least 30 people were reportedly killed and
dozens injured on Wednesday evening in an ammunition shop
explosion in northwestern Pakistan, local newspapers reported here
today.
</P>
<P>
The explosion started at about 7:00 p.m. (local time) and was
followed by a series of blasts in Bajaur Agency, about 80
kilometers northwest of Peshawar, capital of North West Frontier
province, according to the reports. (Pakistan-Blast)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Bosnia's Serb President Biljana Plavsic and Serb
member of the Bosnian presidency Momcilo Krajisnik Wednesday
agreed to stop bickering that would lead to the split of Bosnian
Serbs.
</P>
<P>
The deal came as a result of the mediation of Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic, who met Plavsic and Krajisnik
earlier today to help end the current political
crisis. (Yugoslavia-Bosnian Serb-Agreement) 
