<DOCNO> XIE19970925.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Least Developed Countries' Average Growth Slows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The gross domestic
product (GDP) growth rates in the world's 48 least developed
countries (LDCS) averaged 4.7 percent in 1996, compared with 5.2
percent in 1995, a latest U.N. report has revealed.
</P>
<P>
According to "The Least Developed Countries 1997 Report"
published by the United Nations Conference on Trade and
Development (UNCTAD) here, the slight decline of LDCS' GDP growth
in 1996 is due mainly to a slow down in the average growth rate
of the 33 African LDCS, from 5.4 percent in 1995 to 4.6 percent
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
It also said growth in 1996 in the LDCS group was mitigated by
the fall of several key commodity prices during the last three
quarters, and, more broadly, the continuing steep decline in aid
flows to LDCS.
</P>
<P>
Despite some successful attempts at increasing their export
and diversification of their export commodities, the report
pointed out, many LDCS continue to be highly vulnerable to
commodity price movements in the world market.
</P>
<P>
Most of African LDCS were affected by declines in tropical
food prices (15 percent), minerals (13 percent), coffee (26
percent) and copper (20 percent), according to the report.
</P>
<P>
African LDCS remained over four percent economic growth last
year as a result of their economic policy reforms, while the
average growth rate of Asian and Pacific island LDCS rose
slightly from 4.6 percent in 1995 to 4.8 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The report believed that the Asian LDCS have benefited from
their location in the world's fastest-growing region, saying that
the recent dynamism of the large Asian economies, in particular
India and China, has spilled over into neighboring Asian LDCS
such as Laos, Burma, Cambodia and Nepal, etc.
</P>
<P>
The report foresaw that the growth in the world economy is
expected to remain steady during 1997 and the current sharp rise
in tropical beverage prices will benefit many LDCS.
</P>
<P>
"There is reason to be cautiously optimistic about the
prospects for the majority of the LDCS," the report said.
</P>
<P>
It added that the future of African LDCS is "looking decidely
brighter" because export production has been increased, inflation
rates reduced and reform constantly well implemented in many
African LDCS since the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
However, the report stressed that peace and stability is the
condition of economic development in all LDCS since civil wars
and coups had sent one quarter of LDCS' economies to drop at a
rate of over 20 percent during the period between 1980 and 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
