<HEADLINE> Kenyan Teachers Committed to October 1 Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The Kenya National Union of
Teachers (KNUT) has issued a seven-day strike notice, saying that
teachers all over the country would down their tools on October 1
if their demands were not met by September 30.
</P>
<P>
The new notice sent to Teachers Service Commission (TSC) on
Wednesday followed the expiry of a 21-day notice of strike issued
on September 3.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to TSC, KNUT Secretary-General Ambrose Adongu said
that the strike would go on if the recommendations of the
Teachers Service Review Commission (TSRC) will not have been
implemented in full at the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
The TSRC recommended a salary increase ranging between 150 and
200 percent for the teachers in the east African country and the
minimum pay should be increased from 1,880 Kenyan Shillings
(about 30 U.S. Dollars) per month to 5,640 Shillings (some 90
Dollars).
</P>
<P>
But the Kenyan government agreed to give the teachers an
increment ranging between 10 and 28 percent, which the teachers
union rejected, terming it as "an insult".
</P>
<P>
Most KNUT branches in the country have supported the national
strike call and have vowed to mobilize all teachers to down their
tools from October 1.
</P>
<P>
The KNUT said in the fresh notice that the strike action would
continue until a full settlement was reached on their demands.
</P>
<P>
Yesterday the union met with the officials from the education
and labor ministries to sort out the industry dispute and
Minister of Education Joseph Kamotho is expected to meet KNUT and
TSC officials to discuss this issue further.
</P>
<P>
Kamotho said earlier this month that "surely it is not
realistic for anybody to ask for a 200 percent hike," adding that
workable solution should be found to avert the planned national
strike. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
