<HEADLINE> Kenya Tries to Ease Tourism Crisis on Coast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Three Kenyan cabinet
ministers and Police Commissioner Duncan Wachira are to arrive at
the coastal city of Mombasa today in an attempt to stem the sharp
drop in tourist bookings which threatens to destroy the industry.
</P>
<P>
The ministers, Messrs Protus Momanyi, Katana Ngala and Jackson
Kalweo, are respectively responsible for tourism, lands and
settlement, as well as internal security, the Daily Nation
newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
They are expected to meet stakeholders in tourism on the
coast, which attracted about 70 percent of the visitors touring
the east African country last year, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Tour operators will use the meeting to request the government
for a six-month moratorium on all tax collection including
value-added taxes, telephone and electric charges.
</P>
<P>
The tax waiver is expected to allow the industry to survive
and maintain jobs for Kenyans. Many hotels have laid off staff.
</P>
<P>
The violence at the coast, which has claimed more than 60
lives since August 13, has led to massive cancellation of
bookings in the overseas market.
</P>
<P>
As a result, coastal hotels suffered an unprecedented drop in
bed occupancy rates. Before the violence started, the occupancy
rate averaged a peak of 80-90 percent. This dropped to a record
low of 0-25 percent this week.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, President Daniel arap Moi gave officials a dressing
down over their ineptness in pacifying the industry's players who
have been extremely anxious over the long-running violence at the
Coast.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Kenya Tourist Board Peter Mbugua has also
warned that if the industry collapsed, 150,000 jobs would be lost
together with 25.6 billion Shillings (413 million U.S. Dollars)
lost in foreign exchange earnings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
