<HEADLINE> Hainan Enhances Educational Exchanges With Overseas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Foreign teachers are often
seen at many universities, middle and primary schools, and
kindergartens in south China's Hainan Province. Even some family
tutors are from overseas.
</P>
<P>
Just a few years ago, however, foreign teachers were a rarity
on this island.
</P>
<P>
"Opening up in education is just as important for the growth of
the province as in the economy," said Yuan Lingnan, an official
with the provincial educational department of Hainan, China's
largest special economic zone.
</P>
<P>
Yuan's department has put information about their programs on
the Internet, so as to maintain close ties with overseas.
</P>
<P>
The province received more than 30 visiting scholars from
Germany, Canada and Britain, and introduced nearly 50 foreign
teachers during the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
"However, this still cannot meet the schools' demand," Yuan
said.
</P>
<P>
About 17 schools in Hainan have hired foreign teachers. Some of
the foreign professors even move their families to this scenic
subtropical island.
</P>
<P>
Five British universities signed cooperative agreements with
the province in April. Hainan University, Foreign Trade School and
Farming Machinery School have all had exchanges with institutes
from Canada, the US, Britain and Japan over the past several years.
</P>
<P>
Youngsters are the biggest beneficiary of the province's
educational opening up. The coming of foreign teachers has
upgraded schools' educational quality, and raised students'
enthusiasm for learning.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, students have had more opportunities to study
abroad. Since 1991, the province has sent nearly 200 students to
Japan to study automobile-manufacturing, food processing and
electronics. And more than 70 students have been sent to the US,
Britain and Singapore for further education this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
