<HEADLINE> China, Japan Jointly Study Agricultural Potential in Hebei </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, September 25 (Xinhua) -- A Sino-Japanese
feasibility study will be launched in the Taihang Mountain areas
in north China's Hebei Province next month to determine the
agricultural development potential there.
</P>
<P>
The two-year project will be conducted by both Chinese and
Japanese experts to study soil, rock formations, and climate in
the Mahui River Valleys in Shahe and Wu'an cities, the mountainous
areas in Pingshan county, the Dasha River Valleys, and the
Wanglonggou Valleys in Yixian county.
</P>
<P>
The experts will work out a package plan for the redevelopment
of the areas after the study is finished.
</P>
<P>
The Taihang Mountain area has long been one of the poorest
areas in China.
</P>
<P>
Chinese and Japanese experts have said they will continue to
jointly sponsor agro-development projects, and the Japanese
government will give priority to sponsoring the work with
government loans and financial gifts.  
