<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Chittagong EPZ Thrives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- With low wages and other
facilities, Bangladesh's Chittagong Export Processing Zone (EPZ)
is on the move, creating opportunities for new units and
employment, the Daily Star reported today.
</P>
<P>
The workforce in the zone may rise to 80,000 in the next four
years, while the number of factories is expected to reach 150,
officials from the zone predicted.
</P>
<P>
The zone created 7,000 new jobs in 1996-97, bringing the total
number to 41,000, the officials stated, adding that some 66
percent of them are female.
</P>
<P>
There are now 76 factories in operation, while seven more are
expected to go into production by December this year.
</P>
<P>
"The main attraction for the foreign investors is cheap labor
and other facilities," a zone official pointed out.
</P>
<P>
An apprentice worker gets 22 U.S. dollars a month, unskilled
worker 38 dollars, semi-skilled 45 dollars, and skilled 63
dollars, according to official reports.
</P>
<P>
Trade union activities are completely banned in the zone,
according to the rule governing the zone.
</P>
<P>
Adding to it all are such incentives as a ten-year tax holiday
and duty-free import and export facilities.
</P>
<P>
The Chittagong export processing zone became operational in
1983. So far, 343 plots have been developed, of which 55 percent
have already been allotted for factories, the official stated.
</P>
<P>
The zone has attracted investors from various countries and
regions.
</P>
<P>
The products manufactured by the zone include electronics,
garments, textiles, toys, computers discs, leather products, caps
and bicycles.
</P>
<P>
At present, there are two export processing zones in
Bangladesh. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
