<DOCNO> XIE19970925.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Coffee Losing Competitiveness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 25 (Xinhua) -- African coffee is
steadily losing its competitive edge to Latin American and
Southeast Asian rivals, according to the local press today.
</P>
<P>
Africa's lack of competitiveness has considerably eroded its
share in world robusta's market over the past 20 years, dropping
from 78 to 44 percent, to the advantage of Latin American and
Southeast Asian growers, said a report published by the
International Cooperative Alliance regional office for eastern,
central and southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the sharp decline is historical in that
African growers no longer establish new plantings on fertile
virgin soil, adding that "since 40 percent of African plantations
date from before independence and have not been renewed in many
instances, land is exhausted."
</P>
<P>
Southeast Asia, which is a new comer to coffee growing, has
new plantations producing heavy coffee yields. Latin America has
been through both phases and is now investing in modernization of
its coffee-growing by using improved varieties and advanced
growing techniques including pruning and use of fertilizers.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, many African countries have used coffee income on
parastatal infrastructure to manage coffee exports while at the
same time allowing middlemen a virtual monopoly.
</P>
<P>
"This has left growers at a disadvantage and without
incentive. As as result, coffee harvests of the boom years of the
1970s brought very little benefit either from increased income or
from state involvement," the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
