<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Chief Says World Bank-IMF Meetings Fruitful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Managing Director of the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) Michel Camdessus said here today
that the Annual Meetings of the World Bank and the IMF, which
closed here this morning, were "quite fruitful."
</P>
<P>
"I am very satisfactory with the meetings" and "we are ready to
further international cooperation" in the financial sphere, said
Camdessus at a news conference in the Hong Kong Convention and
Exhibition Center following the closing session of the World
Bank-IMF Annual Meetings.
</P>
<P>
During the past few days, "we have had extensive
thought-provoking discussions about the challenges of global
markets," he said. "We have made substantial headway in equipping
the IMF to help its members meet these challenges."
</P>
<P>
"Recent developments in several Southeast Asian markets have,
of course, been ever present in our minds," he added.
</P>
<P>
As to the results of the meetings, Camdessus said he had
outlined "four points and a half," without specifying.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the closing session, he said that many participants
of the meeting had expressed their conviction that global opening
and integration offer the only path to greater global prosperity.
</P>
<P>
He said the time had come to give the IMF a mandate to promote
the orderly liberalization of capital movements, and a solid
multilateral system for surveillance and financial support is
necessary to be established.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the necessity of anti-corruption and good
governance, adding that the IMF must be ready to respond with its
financial support, if its member-countries need. He praised
Africa's progress in the economic sphere and hopes the Africans
"do more and better."
</P>
<P>
The IMF chief also thanked the Chinese government and the
government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR)
for good preparation and organization of the World Bank-IMF Annual
Meetings.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the closing session, World Bank President James
Wolfensohn told a news conference earlier this morning that the
Annual Meetings were "remarkably successful."
</P>
<P>
"We were able to point out the importance of having these
meetings here in Hong Kong, both to demonstrate the remarkable
achievements of Asia, many discussions about what other parts of
the world could learn from the Asian experience and then, of
course, the reality of the currency situation which reminded us
all that there are some problems that occur from time to time in a
growth pattern and that we have to be ready to deal with them," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
