<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Fish Output Reports Slight Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The world fish production
reached 115.9 million tons in 1996, a 2.9 percent increase over
that of 1995, the U.N. Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO)
said today.
</P>
<P>
The FAO, in the preliminary figures released here today, said
that China continued to be the major world fish producer with a
catch of 27.3 million tons last year, 2.9 million tons more than
that of 1995.
</P>
<P>
More than 50 percent of China's fish output in 1996 comes from
expanding inland aquaculture industry, the FAO said.
</P>
<P>
Other important world fish producers in 1996 were Peru with 9.6
million tons, Chile 6.9 million tons, Japan 6.6 million tons, the
United States 5.9 million tons, India 5.7 million tons, Indonesia
4.2 million tons and Russia 4.6 million tons, the Rome-based FAO
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the world shrimp production stood at some three
million tons, but farmed shrimp production declined because of
diseases, the FAO said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
