<HEADLINE> Indonesia Plans to Boost Electricity Generating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government has
decided to boost its electricity generating capacity by
constructing more power plants to meet the increasing demand in
the country, according to an official source here.
</P>
<P>
The government has initially planned to construct plants that
will have the capacity to produce an additional 12,522 megawatts
of electricity by the end of the sixth five-year development plan
(1994-1999), the Indonesian National Development Information
Office said in its latest publication on Indonesia's economic
condition.
</P>
<P>
"Of the total, plants with the ability to generate 9,522
megawatts will be constructed by State Electric Company (PLN) and
another 3,000 megawatts will be provided through private power
operation," said the publication.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia previously relied on oil in the total energy mix, as
reflected by the fact that oil accounted for 86 percent of
installed power capacity in 1984.
</P>
<P>
But today, the oil share is around 40 percent, and is destined
to further drop to around 31 percent by the sixth five year plan,
the office said, adding that the share of coal in the energy mix
at the same time continued to increase.  
</P>
</TEXT>
