<HEADLINE> Chinese, Thai FMs Discuss Southeast Asia Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese and Thai
foreign ministers today met at U.N. headquarters here and
exchanged views on the economic and political situation in
Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
Qian Qichen, also China's vice premier, told his Thai
counterpart, Prachuab Chaiyasarn, that China, as one of Thailand's
friendly neighbors, is closely watching the financial disturbances
in the Southeast Asian region.
</P>
<P>
He said he believed that countries in that region, including
Thailand, will overcome the difficulties and get their economies
back on a normal track.
</P>
<P>
Prachuab briefed Qian on the efforts being made by the Thai
government to stablize the economy and restore economic growth.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed his gratitude to the Chinese people, who, he
said, had extended their sympathy and help to Thailand.
</P>
<P>
On the Cambodian situation, Qian said Cambodia's internal
affairs should be handled independently by the Cambodian people.
</P>
<P>
The general election in the country should be carried out in a
just and smooth manner and on schedule, Qian said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that different parties would abide by the
spirit of democratic and peaceful solutions advocated by King
Norodom Sihanouk and seek an early restoration of peace.
</P>
<P>
He also showed his appreciation for the efforts made by the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) in seeking
solutions to the Cambodia issue.
</P>
<P>
On regional security, Qian said that China encourages the
increased use of dialogue to promote mutual understanding and
establish mutual trust, which will eventually lead to regional
security.
</P>
<P>
The choice of a military alliance will only achieve the
opposite results, Qian added. 
</P>
