<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank/IMF Annual Meetings End in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The 52nd Annual Meetings of
the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund (IMF) closed
here today, with good organization work of the Chinese government
and the authorities of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(HKSAR) highly appreciated.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the closing session, World Bank President James
Wolfensohn first thanked China and the HKSAR for the environment
and hospitality they have provided.
</P>
<P>
He described the meeting as one related to poverty, to the
"challenge of inclusion".
</P>
<P>
"Poverty is a problem not only for poor countries, but for all
of us," he noted. He urged member countries to address such
fundamental issues as education, health, social development,
environment and infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
"Let's not wait, waiting doesn't help. Let's try to focus on
the issues now," he said.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank president summed up the topics widely discussed
at the meetings, including the recent financial crisis in East
Asia, involvement of the private sector and corruption.
</P>
<P>
Managing Director of the IMF Michel Camdessus in his concluding
remarks spoke highly of "the excellent facilities our hosts have
provided us and the way they have organized everything so
splendidly."
</P>
<P>
"During the past few days, we have had extensive,
thought-provoking discussions about the challenges of global
markets. And we have made substantial headway in equipping the IMF
to help its members meet these challenge," he said.
</P>
<P>
Four major themes emerged from the "fruitful" meeting, he noted.
</P>
<P>
First, the conviction has been expressed that global opening
and integration offer the only path to greater global prosperity.
</P>
<P>
Second, it is reconfirmed that time has come to give the Fund a
mandate to promote the orderly liberalization of capital
movements, and thereby add a new chapter to the Bretton Woods
agreement.
</P>
<P>
The third is the vital importance that is attached to good
governance in all its dimensions.
</P>
<P>
And finally, members have emphasized that when problems do
emerge, as surely they will continue to do, the Fund must be ready
to respond with its financial support.
</P>
<P>
At around 10:40 a.m. Chairman of the Annual Meetings Mohammed
K. Khirbash, who is also governor from the United Arab Emirates,
announced the meetings adjourned.
</P>
<P>
The next joint meetings of the two international financial
institutions will be held in Washington, D.C. with the Austrian
governor assuming the post of chairman.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970925.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Poverty Eradication Succeeding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's poverty
alleviation effort is on track, as evidenced by the fact that the
number of poor families in the archipelago is continually on the
decline, according to a census issued here today.
</P>
<P>
The census conducted recently by the government on Indonesia's
43 million families showed that only 19.41 percent are considered
poor -- a drop of 23.38 percent compared with the 41 million
families polled last year.
</P>
<P>
A family is considered poor if it is unable to meet its basic
food, clothing and housing needs, said the census.
</P>
<P>
Since the first Five-Year Development Plan (1969-1974),
Indonesia has continually boosted development with an emphasis on
the improvement of people's welfare and the attainment of high
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Under a 1993 presidential decree, the government provided each
of the 22,000 backward villages in the country with interest-free
loans totaling 20 million rupiah (6,600 U.S. dollars) per year as
working capital for a three-year period.
</P>
<P>
President Soeharto issued another decree in 1996 to speed up
the poverty alleviation effort through the so-called prosperous
family movement program.
</P>
<P>
Through its poverty alleviation program, Indonesia has been
successful in slashing the number of poor people from 25.9 million
(13.6 percent of the total population) in 1993 to 22.5 million (11
percent) in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The government hoped that no Indonesian will live in poverty by
the end of the Seventh Five-Year Development Plan (1999-2004).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970925.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Massive Cheating in Italian Disabled Subsidies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Nearly one in every four people
receiving a government subsidy for the disabled in Italy is doing
so by pretending to be a handicapped person, the Italian Ministry
of the Treasury said after a national survey.
</P>
<P>
The ministry's own doctors were dispatched throughout the
country to conduct the survey. By the end of June, they had
administered health examinations to more than 71,000 reportedly
disabled people.
</P>
<P>
In the survey, the doctors found that about 24 percent of these
people, or 17,000 of them, were not handicapped. Their subsidies
have been suspended.
</P>
<P>
The survey is part of the government's strategy to cut the
financial deficit.
</P>
<P>
The amount of money saved from discontinuing the subsidies
following the survey is estimated to be about 200 billion lire
(about 110 million U.S. dollars); so the ministry has decided to
continue the health check.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ministry has also begun to conduct another
national survey on the use of government vehicles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
