<DOCNO> XIE19970925.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: More Countries Offer to Fight Fire in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- More countries are now
offering help to Indonesia in fighting forest fires raging in
Kalimantan, Sumatra and other places in the country, official
sources from the Ministry of Forestry said here today.
</P>
<P>
The forest fires, which started in mid August, have now caused
choking smoke to begin engulfing areas as distant as the popular
Thai resort of Phuket and the Philippine capital of Manila.
Malaysia and Singapore were affected by the haze of forest fires
in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Japan donated 300 sets of jet shooters and water
pumps, and is considering dispatching an emergency relief and
forest fire expert team to help fight fires in the two islands
(Sumatra and Kalimantan), the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Malaysia also decided to send air force transport
planes to water-bomb forest fires and dispatch extra personnel to
reinforce 1,200 fire fighters dispatched on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Philippine President Fidel Ramos on Wednesday ordered a
government mobilization to tackle the smoke from forest fires and
asked Foreign Secretary Domingo Siazon to meet his counterparts
from Indonesia, Malaysia, Singapore and Brunei to determine what
they can do to settle the problems.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian Forest Minister Djamaludin Suryohadikusumo claimed
Wednesday that fire fighters deployed to put out the blaze should
soon have the upper hand.
</P>
<P>
The ministry deployed 8,437 fire fighters divided into 560
teams in 17 provinces to handle the fires in forest concession
areas and industrial timber estates, he said.
</P>
<P>
With their expertise backed by various equipment, the fire
fighters could keep the fire under control, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has also reportedly set aside 1.07 million US
dollars to handle the forest fires.
</P>
<P>
Data showed that until September 19, more than 400,000 hectares
of forest areas had been destroyed in the fires since mid August.
More than one hundred plantation firms in the country were accused
of using fire in land clearing which was believed to be the major
cause of the widespread fires.
</P>
<P>
The smog has put 20 million people in danger of respiratory
problems in the region. It has left two dead in Sumatra.
</P>
<P>
The smog has already halted air traffic, causing 800 flight
delays and at least seven boat collisions on central Kalimantan's
Mahakam river in the last few weeks.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, tourism official Wuryastuti Sunarto said Wednesday
the Tourism Promotion Board was already predicting that Indonesia
would fall short of its 1997 tourism target of 5.7 million foreign
visitors as a result of the haze.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
