<HEADLINE> Chinese, French Foreign Ministers Meet in New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese and French
foreign ministers held talks here today on bilateral relations
between their two countries during a meeting at the United Nations
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
Qian Qichen, also Chinese vice premier, said that during the
May visit to China by French President Jacques Chirac's, leaders
of the two countries decided to establish partnership links that
would be beneficial to both countries in the 21st century. The
newly formed French government reaffirmed that France would
continue to engage in fulfilling this target, Qian said.
</P>
<P>
Qian said that as the world grows in diversification, it is of
mutual interest and significant to the world for the two countries
to set up such a partnership, especially since China and France
are permanent members of the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Qian said that because of frequent visits by the leaders of the
two countries, bilateral relations are growing. Cooperation in
economics, trade, science and culture has been very
successful.
</P>
<P>
Qian also said he hoped that China and the European Union could
work together equally and with mutual respect in joint efforts to
carry out more exchanges.
</P>
<P>
In the meeting, French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine agreed
on Qian's view of the world situation, saying France and China
should strengthen their ties in the changing world. He emphasized
that the French government will continue to carry out its goodwill
policy towards China and place the development of a well-rounded
partnership with China in an especially important position.
</P>
</TEXT>
