<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Hosts Large Postage Culture Festival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, September 25 (Xinhua) -- A large-scale festival to
celebrate the culture of post offices will be held in
Gaoyou city in east China's Jiangsu Province on October 9-10.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the festival, jointly sponsored by the Ministry
of Posts and Telecommunications, the provincial government of
Jiangsu and the State Bureau of Cultural Relics, is to promote the
development of the postal business in China and boost the local
economy.
</P>
<P>
Gaoyou, which means "the high building of posts" in Chinese, is
the only city out of the over 2,000 cities and counties in China
to be named after the postal system.
</P>
<P>
According to historical documents, it has been about 2,220
years since the first post office was set up in Gaoyou during
ancient China's Qin Dynasty (from 221 to 207 BC).
</P>
<P>
Sources say stamp auctions and exhibitions and symposiums on
postage culture will be held during the festival, while
businessmen from China and abroad will also be invited to
participate in a series of business activities.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Ministry of Posts and Telecommunications will
issue a set of postcards to mark the 22nd Symposium of the
Universal Postal Union to be held in China later this year.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
