<DOCNO> XIE19970925.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Seals Polluted Areas in Former US Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Clark
Development Corporation has sealed off at least 12 danger spots at
the former US Air Force base, which were found to have varying
degrees of toxicity, local newspaper The Philippine Star reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Romeo David, president of the corporation, said that the Clark
risk areas have been cordoned off and covered with new topsoil and
plastic "to prevent dermal contact, ingestion and inhalation of
the contaminants" by humans.
</P>
<P>
The Asia Star Weston International, which conducted the
toxicity tests at the former Clark Air Base, identified three
sites as "potentially high risk", five as "medium risk" and four
as "low risk", the Star said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a former commanding officer of the US aircraft
carrier USS Midway and the Pacific-US Task Force expressed belief
that the Subic Bay Freeport, formerly a US naval base, might have
more serious levels of toxic waste contamination.
</P>
<P>
After the withdrawal of US military forces from the Philippine
territory in 1992, toxic waste and environmental damage were found
at the two former bases.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government has requested the US to clean up
Subic and Clark, but so far has not received any reply from
Washington.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
