<HEADLINE> Hun Sen Asks for Meeting with Annan on UN Seat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Cambodian Second Prime Minister
Hun Sen said today that he wants a talk with
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan on the issue of his country's
U.N. seat before he could decide to go New York and attend the
on-going sessions of the 52nd General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
"New York is still my goal, but I will go when the secretary-
general of the United Nations grants me a meeting" on Cambodia's
seat which the world body announced vacant last Friday, Hun Sen
said at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
The Cambodian Foreign Ministry in a statement has accused the
the U.N. General Assembly of interfering in Cambodia's internal
affairs.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia's First Prime Minister Ung Huot left Sunday for New
York to press his government's case at the General Assembly. Hun
Sen would follow Ung Huot as planned originally.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen threatened that Cambodia might reject a U.N. role in
monitoring its general elections due on May 23, 1998 if its seat
in the General Assembly is kept vacant.
</P>
<P>
"We have agreed to give the U.N. a coordinating role in
overseeing the elections," he said. But "I do not see how the
United Nations can play this coordinating role since it has
decided to leave our seat empty. It should think if it wants to
play a certain role and work with us."
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen also said that Prince Norodom Ranariddh and former
Finance Minister Sam Rainsy were welcome to return to Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen said that he will ensure their safety if they choose to
return.
</P>
<P>
Prince Ranariddh is welcome to come back to Cambodia and
participate in the elections as he has not been charged in court,
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
