<HEADLINE> Bosnia's Plavsic, Krajisnik Reach Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Bosnia's Serb President
Biljana Plavsic and Serb member of the Bosnian presidency Momcilo
Krajisnik today agreed to stop bickering that would lead to the
split of Bosnian Serbs.
</P>
<P>
The deal came as a result of the mediation of Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic, who met Plavsic and Krajisnik
earlier today to help end the current political crisis.
</P>
<P>
Under their accord, Plavsic and Krajisnik agreed to take all
necessary steps to stop any conflicts that would threaten the
unity of Bosnian Serbs.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to hold elections for the republic's parliament on
November 15, and for the presidency and the Serb member of the
three-man Bosnian presidency on December 17.
</P>
<P>
The current political crisis among the Bosnian Serb leadership
began in early July, when Plavsic dissolved the parliament despite
strong opposition from it.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Plavsic's exposure of high-level corruption led to
further conflict with Bosnian Serb hard-liners, who expelled her
from the Serb Social Democratic Party and demanded her resignation
as president. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
