<DOCNO> XIE19970925.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Threatened by Desertification </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Italy is threatened by a
phenomenon known as desertification as over a quarter of its
territory has the risk of being reduced to dry and barren lands.
</P>
<P>
Data released here today at a meeting show that 27 percent of
Italian territory is considered as risking desertification -- a
change of arable land into a desert from either natural causes or
human activity.
</P>
<P>
Today's meeting, which was held in preparation for the first
world conference on desertification here next week, was.attended
by Italian Foreign Undersecretary Piero Fassino and Undersecretary
for Environment Valerio Calzolaio.
</P>
<P>
Calzolaio said that a plan of action for the Mediterranean
region will emerge from the United Nations conference to be held
from September 30 to October 10.
</P>
<P>
According to U.N. figures, desertification causes an annual
revenue loss of 42 million U.S. dollars worldwide and affects 250
million people all over the world.
</P>
<P>
A billion more people are at risk, said Calzolaio.
</P>
<P>
In North America, desertification engulfs 74 percent of the
land while 73 percent of the African continent is threatened, he
said.
</P>
<P>
In Europe, Italy and Spain need to address the problem more
seriously and the risk of desertification in Asia and South
America is increasing, he said.
</P>
<P>
Italy has contributed 1,750 billion lire (one billion
U.S. dollars) to developing countries to fund anti-desertification
projects, said Calzolaio.
</P>
<P>
Next week's conference will be attended by more than a thousand
delegates including heads of state, ministers and diplomats.
</P>
<P>
The conference aims to find ways to implements the
Desertification Convention adopted on December 29, 1996 and
already ratified by 108 countries.
</P>
<P>
The countries who signed the Convention pledge to work out a
long-term strategy to fight desertification based on international
cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970925.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share-Holding System Contributes to Hainan's Prosperity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Share-holding companies in
south China's Hainan Province has mushroomed in number,
contributing greatly to local economic development.
</P>
<P>
Some 130 share-holding companies have issued shares valued at
23 billion yuan, with 19 companies listed on stock exchanges at
home or abroad.
</P>
<P>
The rebirth of securities markets has provided local
enterprises with new sources of capital and has promoted the rapid
development in wide-ranging sectors, including energy, agriculture,
telecommunications, expressways and airports.
</P>
<P>
A series of major achievements has prompted the Hainan provincial
government to outline a general program calling for further
expansion of the share-holding system.
</P>
<P>
The program calls for the large-scale introduction of the joint
stock system and the expansion of infrastructure and pillar
industries.
</P>
<P>
A number of state-owned share-holding enterprise groups will be
formed to enhance competitiveness and raise economic
returns.
</P>
<P>
Hainan, located at the juncture of the South China Sea and the
Beibu Bay, is the nation's second largest island after Taiwan and
largest Special Economic Zone. Hainan was granted provincial
status in April 1988. 
</P>
</TEXT>
