<BODY>
<HEADLINE> URGENT: WB/IMF Annual Meetings End in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The 1997 Annual Meetings of
the World Bank Group and the International Monetary Fund (IMF)
ended here this morning after three days of discussion.
</P>
<P>
Participants from 181 countries exchanged views and ideas on a
wide range of financial issues including the world economic
situation, recent Southeast Asian currency turmoil, reforms in
China, free capital flow, enhanced surveillance, increase in IMF
quotas (special drawing rights), assistance to the poorest
countries and private sector participation in infrastructure
projects.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Premier Li Peng delivered a speech at the opening of
the annual meetings, putting forward six propositions regarding
international cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The 1997 annual meetings, the biggest event in WB/IMF history,
drew nearly 20,000 people from all parts of the world as they were
preceded by a string of seminars and numerous bilateral and
multilateral talks among high-ranking government officials,
policy-makers, bankers, business executives, economists and
researchers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
