<DOCNO> XIE19970925.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panama's Congress Debates Jail Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The Congress of Panama is
preparing to debate jail reform measures that will help alleviate
chaos in the country's overcrowded prisons.
</P>
<P>
The decision to debate reform measures was made after recent
prison riots resulted in the escape of 11 dangerous convicts from
one of Panama's top security prisons.
</P>
<P>
The Minister of State and Justice Raul Montenegro submitted a
draft bill package to the Legislative Assembly designed to improve
the country's penitentiary system.
</P>
<P>
One of the issues suggested in the draft bill is to release
unsentenced detainees, or those incarcerated as a preventive
measure, in order to put an end to the overcrowding and chaos in
the countryy's prison system.
</P>
<P>
Montenegro said the law, if enacted, would require the release
of thousands of unsentenced detainees who are languishing in
prison because of inefficiency and judicial procedures that have
bogged down.
</P>
<P>
"The draft bill should be a useful tool to alleviate current
turmoil in the penitentiary system, which lately has demonstrated
extreme violence and fierce riots," Montenegro said.
</P>
<P>
But he said the reform must not be regarded as an exoneration
act, nor a general amnesty. Penal action would continue in each
case until the judical processes were resolved.
</P>
<P>
"La Joya" jail, which bears the name of an island located in
the Pacific, was considered the country's top-security prison.
</P>
<P>
In January, a riot occurred there. The inmates took guards as
hostages and asked for negotiations to accelerate their judicial
procedures.
</P>
<P>
The inmates calmed down after authorities promised to review
the penitentiary system and improve jail conditions.
</P>
<P>
However, the riot occurred again early this week, during which
time 11 dangerous prisoners, incarcerated on charges of murder,
drug-trafficking and rape, succeeded in escaping.
</P>
<P>
President Ernesto Perez Balladares ordered the National Police
to intervene in the control of jails across the country that
harbor more than 7,600 inmates.
</P>
<P>
The Police Director Jose Luis Sosa regarded the presidential
measure as "accurate" and promised to bring the problems of
drug-trafficking, weapons and abuse of power in prisons under
control.
</P>
<P>
"I will carry out the president's command to bring discipline
to prisons," he said.
</P>
<P>
Sosa also set a deadline for the 11 fugitives at large, urging
them to surrender. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
