<DOCNO> XIE19970925.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qinghai Herdsmen Fight Against Disasters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Herdsmen in northwest China's
Qinghai province have been busy planting new grass, setting up
fences to save parts of the grassland for spring or winter
herding, building sheds to prevent animals from suffering
illnesses from the cold or freezing to death.
</P>
<P>
These are some of a series of projects launched by Qinghua
province in the pastureland, aiming to improve defences against
natural calamities and raising herdsmen's living standards, acting
provincial governor Bai Enpei was quoted by today's China Daily as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Qinghai is one of China's five major animal husbandry
production bases. Its total meat output in 1996 reached 187,200
tons. However, the province's animal husbandry industry remains
vulnerable to natural disasters. To this high-land province,
winter and spring often mean that large numbers of domestic
animals dies as pastures wither. Frequent snowstorms only worsen
the situation. The disasters take a heavy toll on the herdsmen,
their families and their livelihood.
</P>
<P>
Bai said that Qinghai also plans to spend another 10 years
constructing highways to link all villages and providing
electricity and water for all herders' families.
</P>
<P>
A total of 423 million yuan (51 million US dollars) was
invested in grassland infrastructure development from 1992 to
1996. Half the funds were raised by herdsmen and through bank
loans.
</P>
<P>
Currently 10.4 percent of herding families in the province have
benefited from these projects and 66,800 herding families, or two
thirds of the total in the province, have settled down.
</P>
<P>
To speed up the development of animal husbandry, provincial
authorities have promised herdsmen that the grasslands' policy of
household responsibility will remain unchanged for another 50
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
