<HEADLINE> Thai Private Sector Supports Opening Fish Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's private sector
supports the liberalization of trade in the fish and fish products
sector, according to the Bangkok Post today.
</P>
<P>
The Thai private sector also supports free market in sugar,
canned and processed fruit and vegetables, gems and jewelry, and
pulp industries, according to Vithun Tulyanond, deputy
director-general of the Business Economics Department.
</P>
<P>
But Thailand's private sector and the Fisheries Department of
the Agriculture Ministry are opposed to New Zealand's initiatives
to include liberalizing trade in live fish and coral, for fear of
causing damage to the environment.
</P>
<P>
Import tariffs on fish, fish products and canned seafood would
be reduced ahead of the Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation's
(APEC's) deadline of 2010 for developed economies and 2020 for
developing ones provided APEC members submitted their proposals
before APEC's November meeting in Canada.
</P>
<P>
Vithun also said that Thai fish meal manufacturers also backs
liberalization of fish meal trade as local supply cannot meet
demand and the home-made product has a lower protein content than
that of imports.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
