<HEADLINE> Malaysian PM Leaves for Latin America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 25 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad left here late last night on a 10-day visit to
four Latin-American countries of Cuba, Chile, Uruguay and
Argentina to strengthen ties between Malaysia and these countries.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir's Latin American tour is part of ongoing efforts to
tap new markets and enhance South-South cooperation, Foreign
Ministry officials said.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir is scheduled to have a stopover in Madrid en route to
Havana where he will call on his Spanish counterpart Jose Maria
Aznar.
</P>
<P>
In Cuba, his first official visit to the country at the
invitation of President Fidel Castro, Mahathir will have a meeting
with Castro to explore opportunities for trade and investment
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Three agreements -- one on visa abolition, the second on
promotion and reciprocal protection of investment and the third on
trade -- will be signed to mark the beginning of a new phase in
Malaysia-Cuba relations, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
After his two-day stay in Cuba, Mahathir will proceed to Chile
where he will attend the 12th Pacific Economic Cooperation Council
(PECC) in Santiago.
</P>
<P>
From Santiago, Mahathir will go on to Montevideo, Uruguay, for
a two-day official trip from October 1 to 2 after which he will
wind up his tour with a three-day visit to Argentina where he is
scheduled to speak at the inauguration of the ASEAN-Mercosur
Business Council.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir, who is expected to be back in Kuala Lumpur on October
6, is being accompanied by an official delegation comprising Works
Minister S.Samy Vellu, International Trade and Industry Minister
Rafidah Aziz, and Housing and Local Government Minister Ting Chew
Peh.
</P>
<P>
Also accompanying Mahathir is a 70-member business delegation
led by Malaysia Airlines chairman Tajudin Ramli. 
</P>
