<HEADLINE> North China Power Supplier Gets Exclusive-Dealer License </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Power
Industry issued a power supply business license to North China
Power Group Co. Wednesday in Beijing, "China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
Under the license, the company has the exclusive right to
supply power to Beijing, Tianjin and northern Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
It is a significant step to reform China's power management
system, the Ministry of Power Industry is quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
According to the Electric Power Law that officially went into
effect in April 1996, China will implement a new power supply
system in which a power supplier obtains a license from the
ministry and its subordinate institutions for being an exclusive
dealer of power supply to a certain region.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Power Industry is dividing the country into
different power supply business regions, a process that is
expected to be completed by the end of the year, said the official.
</P>
<P>
The new system will bring order to the power supply market,
avoid over-heated competition and coordinate the development of
large and small power grids, said the official.
</P>
<P>
China is expected to interconnect almost all of its power grids
before the year 2020. To achieve the goal, it created the China
Power Grid Development Ltd Corp. in June 1996.
</P>
<P>
To date, the country now has 11 power grids with an installed
generating capacity of over one million kilowatts each.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
