<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank-IMF Meeting Successful: Wolfensohn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank President,
James Wolfensohn, said here this morning that the annual meetings
of the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund (IMF) to be
closed here later today, had scored many achievements.
</P>
<P>
The participants of the meetings have discussed a lot of
problems and made a number of decisions, said Wolfensohn at a news
conference in the Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition Center,
prior to the closing session of the World Bank/IMF meetings.
</P>
<P>
He said, for example, the finance ministers from over 180
member-countries discussed at the meetings the recent financial
crisis in Thailand and agreed to make efforts to improve banking
and financial systems, particularly in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
At the same news conference, Executive Vice-President of the
Multilateral Investment Guarantee Agency (MIGA) Akira Lida said
that the MIGA was ready to encourage the flow of foreign private
investments to developing countries both by providing guarantees
against political risks to foreign investors and also technical
assistance to host developing countries in order to improve their
ability to attract foreign investments.
</P>
<P>
Responding to questions, Wolfensohn said he shared the views
expressed in Chinese Premier Li Peng's address to the meetings
over the issue of how to help the developing countries achieve
economic growth and social stability.
</P>
<P>
Praising the decision made by the Communist Party of China
(CPC) days earlier in its 15th National Congress on deepening
reform of state-run enterprises, he expressed his thanks to the
Chinese government for the warm reception during the World
Bank/IMF meetings.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Wolfensohn reiterated that the World Bank and the IMF
handle only economic issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
