<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukrainian Parliament Adopts New Election Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The Ukrainian Supreme Soviet
(parliament) adopted a new election law today after a marathon
debate in the 450-seat legislative body.
</P>
<P>
The new electoral system, which has been debated 15 times since
November 1993, was passed with the backing of 230 deputies.
</P>
<P>
An element of proportional representation was introduced into
the electoral law. Under it, 225 members will be elected in
single-seat constituencies while the other 225 seats will be
allotted proportionally according to party lists.
</P>
<P>
The present single-seat constituency system has been blamed for
a proliferation of weak political parties and a disorganized
parliament where factional loyalties change frequently.
</P>
<P>
The old law invalidates any vote where the turnout does not
reach 50 percent or where the leading candidate does not get half
of all the votes cast.
</P>
<P>
The new system requires a minimum turnout of 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
Because the new law reserves half of the seats for members
elected from national party lists based on those parties' share of
the vote, the law was greeted with strong resistance from
unaffiliated lawmakers who want to keep the old system intact.
</P>
<P>
The old law tends to favor candidates who lack national party
ties but wield real power within their election districts.
</P>
<P>
"Party list will leave formation of the parliament in the hands
of party leaders rather than voters," said Mykhailo Chechetov of
the Social Market Choice. "It is party leaders who will decide
upon election who of their members should enter the Supreme
Soviet."
</P>
<P>
Party leaders, however, regard the new election law as a
progress toward a full-fledged multi-party democracy.
</P>
<P>
"We have to adopt the bill favoring parties if we want to have
a capable and effective parliament," said Rukh leader Vyacheslav
Chornovil.
</P>
<P>
Communist lawmaker Valery Mishura, who drafted the new law,
agreed that lawmakers without a party affiliation weaken the
legislature, saying that "half of our parliament is party members,
and the other half can be shaped to anyone's liking." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
