<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 25 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Australian newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The Australian:
</P>
<P>
-- Prime Minister John Howard forced senior ministers John
Sharp and David Jull to resign yesterday over false travel
allowance claims, leaving his government facing its third
ministerial reshuffle within a year.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald
</P>
<P>
-- Prime Minister John Howard is under intense backbench
pressure for a major ministerial reshuffle after two ministers
resigned yesterday amid allegations of a cover-up over
wrongly-claimed travel allowances.
</P>
<P>
The Age
</P>
<P>
-- Former governor general Bill Hayden has opposed the campaign
for Australia to become a republic, but has denied claims he is
monarchist. He said he believed in maintaining the status quo and
did not think becoming a republic would benefit Australia.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review
</P>
<P>
-- Australia's main shipping employers are moving closer to an
agreement with maritime unions on labor reforms designed to reduce
crew costs and open the way for company-level employment of
blue-collar seafarers.  
