<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, Japanese Foreign Ministers Talk over Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Japan and the United
States should strictly limit their defense cooperation within
their bilateral scope, Chinese Foreign Minister Qian Qichen said
here today.
</P>
<P>
The arrangement should not be spread out and should not arouse
any uneasiness among the neighboring countries of Japan, Qian told
Japanese Foreign Minister Keizo Obuchi during their meeting at the
United Nations headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Japan jointly announced a new guidelines
for the U.S.-Japan Defense Cooperation in New York on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Qian, also Chinese Vice-Premier, reiterated China's stand on
such guidelines, saying that the security arrangement between
Japan and the U.S. was a bilateral one created under a specific
historical background. Therefore, it should be strictly confined
to the scope between these two countries, Qian said.
</P>
<P>
Cui Tiankai, the spokesman for the Chinese Ministry of Foreign
Affairs, briefed reporters on the meeting between the two foreign
ministers. He said that both of the two ministers expressed their
will to make joint efforts to promote a steady progress of the
Sino-Japanese relations.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi said that Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto
reconfirmed, during his China visit earlier this month, that Japan
would develop Japan-China relations under the principles set in
the Sino-Japanese Joint Statement and the Sino-Japanese Treaty of
Peace and Friendship. He also told Chinese leaders that Japan will
oppose the "two Chinas" policy and Taiwan independence.
</P>
<P>
Qian said that the Chinese and Japanese leaders did confirmed
the principles and spirit embodied in the two documents, having
agreed to further the neighborly friendly links.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that Qian expressed the belief there would
be new progress in the bilateral meetings provided that the two
sides strictly abide by the principles set in the joint statement
and the peace and friendship treaty.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign ministers also mentioned the visit to Japan by
Chinese Premier Li Peng in November this year, according to the
spokesman. Both agreed that the exchanges of high-level visit
would play an active role in improving and developing the
bilateral relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
