<DOCNO> XIE19970925.0298 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Japan Working on Guidelines Details </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 24 (Xinhua) -- U.S. and Japanese defense
ministers started their discussions on Wednesday on an agreement
on bilateral planning directives following their approval of the
new guidelines for U.S.-Japan defense cooperation in New York.
</P>
<P>
Before his talks with Japanese Defense Minister Fumio Kyuma at
the Pentagon, U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen told reporters
that the bilateral planning directives "will instruct our military
to begin working together on details of future cooperation in
times of peace and in times of crisis."
</P>
<P>
Cohen said he will visit japan later in November to review
whether there is any progress made for the implementation of the
new guidelines, which would allow japan to give key military
support to U.S. forces in what they call an Asian crisis.
</P>
<P>
Under the guidelines, Japan would for the first time since the
World War Two engage in military activities outside its borders in
military conflicts involving the United States.
</P>
<P>
Kyuma said the expansion in U.S.-Japan military cooperation in
Asia would not violate Tokyo's restraints on use of its powerful
armed forces.
</P>
<P>
"The guidelines are not going to alter the interpretation of
the Japanese Constitution. So I would see no problem of these new
guidelines in relation with our Constitution," Kyuma said in his
answer to a reporter's question.
</P>
<P>
The guidelines for future political decisions are not detailed,
and both Cohen and Kyuma said they would work quickly to draw up
firm contingency planning.
</P>
<P>
And the contingency plans would contain such specifics as
Japanese military and commercial ports or airfields would be
available to U.S. forces in a war in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Asian countries are watching warily the intensified security
ties between the United States and Japan. They are concerned the
"robust and dynamic military alliance" between Washington and
Tokyo could constitute grave threats to their security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970925.0299 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentina on Reform of UN Security Council </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The reform of the
Security Council of the United Nations should make the
organization a more democratic and representative body, D.Guido Di
Tella, the Minister of Foreign Affairs, said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the fifty-second session of the General Assembly,
the Foreign Minister said that the composition of the Security
Council in 1945 was consonant with the reality prevailing at the
end of the Second World War, and Argentina was in the view there
was not yet a general Agreement concerning the increase in the
number of permanent members.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said the reform of the Security Council
should make the organization a more democratic and
representative body. To reach that goal, each region would need
to arrive at a compromise free of pressures or haste.
</P>
<P>
He said in the case of Latin America and the Caribbean, the
summit of heads of States of the Rio Group agreed that the
region itself would have to decide how to fill the seats
assigned to it, and Argentina was of the view that an open ended
mechanism of rotation needed to be established as it would
enable the participation of all those states who had shown their
commitment to and respect for the Charter.
</P>
<P>
He stressed this mechanism would avoid discriminations
against those states bearing greater financial responsibilities,
and those responsibilities could even be increased for the
rotating states.
</P>
<P>
He added that Argentina's position was only aimed at favoring
an ample participation by all the states of the region without
exclusions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970925.0300 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonn Approves Bill to Prepare for Euro Transition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The German cabinet today
approved a draft legislation designed mainly to prepare German
companies for the planned 1999 introduction of the single European
currency, the Euro.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposed law, which still have to be endorsed by the
parliament, Germany companies would be able to account their
shares and capital in the Euro from January 1, 1999, but this will
not be compulsory until 2002 when the Euro is due to formally
replace national currencies of its member states.
</P>
<P>
For all fiscal years after January 1, 1998, German companies
would also be allowed to do their annual accounts in the single
currency.
</P>
<P>
The legislation, which matches the legal changes in other EU
countries preparing for the Euro, also paves the way for German
bourses to adjust to the single currency up from January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
"Given the widespread uncertainty and fears about the Euro
conversion, this law will provide the necessary legal certainty in
Germany," said German Justice Minister Edzard Schmidt-Jortzig
today in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he also expressed the confidence that the Euro will
be launched punctually on January 1, 1999 with Germany as one of
its founding members.
</P>
<P>
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl today also made a talk to the
Euro, saying that he would never give in to the widespread
Euro-sceptism in his country.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on opinion polls in recent years which have
repeatedly shown that a majority of Germans are unwilling to give
up their rock-hard D-mark for the Euro, Kohl said: "Polling data
cannot hold us back from doing what has been recognized as right.
Otherwise, we would fail to fulfil our responsibility." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
