<HEADLINE> Ulster New Hope of Talks Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 24 (Xinhua) - Most observers on Northern
Ireland expected today that Sinn Fein, the political party of the
Irish Republican Army (IRA) will be allowed to stay in the peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
The Ulster Unionist Party (UUP), the chief party of the
pro-british majority Protestants, on Tuesday called for Sinn Fein
to be thrown out.
</P>
<P>
They described Sinn Fein leaders as "godfathers of terrorism"
and said they were angry that republicans were being allowed to
the table while guerrilla held on to their weapons in Northern
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
However, the observers expect that Sinn Fein will be allowed to
stay in the talks as Britain and Ireland are trying to broaden the
talks to lay the basis for a lasting settlement that would be put
to referendums next May.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Belfast said that a round-table session of the
talks was adjourned three times today to allow for fine-tuning an
Anglo-Irish proposal for moving current preliminary discussions
into full-scale negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Some sources at the talks predicted that the process was edging
towards a major breakthrough which could lead to talks on the
future of Northern Ireland by next Monday.
</P>
<P>
Substantive talks on the province moved a step closer as the
parties involved looked set to sign a deal to keep the UUP and
Sinn Fein at the table, according to a BBC report tonight.
</P>
<P>
The UUP appears to have softened their line on decomissioning.
Under the deal, which the UUP is expected to sign, arms will not
have to be handed over ahead of a settlement, BBC added.
</P>
<P>
Unionist spokesmen said they had made progress but denied that
they had watered-down their long-standing demand for an early
handover.
</P>
<P>
UUP leader David Trimble also said: "It's not ideal. But
decomissioning is a live issue that will not be sidelined."
</P>
</TEXT>
