<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Sells 4 Mine Sweepers to Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- France has sold four retired
mine sweepers to Turkey for about 50 million US dollars, said
Turkish and French officials today.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the Turkish Defense Ministry and the French Naval
Construction Management International (DCNI) signed the contract
today in Ankara.
</P>
<P>
The 500-ton "Circe" type mine-sweepers have just retired from
the French navy and will be handed over to the Turkish navy in
1998 after undergoing technological renovations at the Brest navy
shipyard.
</P>
<P>
The mine-sweepers will be equipped with a tactic information
treatment system, and sub-marine piloted vehicles for detecting
and destroying mines, said DCNI in a communique.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time for France to sell armaments to Turkish
navy, which mainly buys its armaments from Germany and the United
States.
</P>
<P>
French officials said that France is seeking contracts with the
Turkish army on the sale of assault helicopters, armored vehicles
and anti-tank missiles.
</P>
<P>
The Franco-German Eurocopter company signed with Turkey in
February a 430 million dollar contract ordering 30 Cougar back-up
and emergency rescue helicopters.
</P>
<P>
Eurocopter is competing with American, Italian and Russian
companies for a 3 billion dollar contract for a squad of 145
assault helicopters for the Turkish army.
</P>
<P>
The French army equipment producing group GICAT is also
competing with 10 other international companies for a 5 billion
dollar contract on the construction of 1,000 tanks with Turkish
companies.
</P>
<P>
The Aerospatiale airspace group is close to a contract with
Turkey on building short-distance Eryx anti-tank missiles for the
Turkish army, said French and Turkish officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
