<HEADLINE> Crete Summit Likely Another Chance for Greek-Turkish Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Greece today said that the
Balkan summit on Crete in early November might provide Athens and
Ankara with another chance to better their relations.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that the summit of Balkan nations in Crete where there
is a scheduled meeting between Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis
and his Turkish counterpart Mesut Yilmaz will bring results,"
Greek government spokesman Dimitris Reppas said here today.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Turkey lost a chance to improve their strained
relations for decades following a fruitless meeting between Greek
Foreign Minister Theodoros Pangalos and his Turkish counterpart,
Ismail Cem, in New York Tuesday night on the sidelines of the U.N.
General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
It was the first high-level meeting between the two neighboring
countries since the signing of the Madrid communique in early
July, which drew broad guidelines for Greek-Turkish relations.
</P>
<P>
Reppas attributed the failure of the Pangalos-Cem meeting to
Turkey's stance, saying that Turkey refused to take the step which
would lead it to deal with the issue of the Aegean islet of Imia.
</P>
<P>
In January 1996, the two countries nearly went to war after
Ankara questioned Athens' sovereignty over the uninhabited islet
in the Aegean sea.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman stressed that the Madrid communique indicated
that Turkey takes its claim over Imia to international
jurisdiction, which it has not done. 
</P>
</TEXT>
